<HEADLINE> Tunisia to Raise Grain Products Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Tunisian government has
decided to raise the sale prices of some grain products as of
Thursday in a bid to further cut down expenditures on the Public
Fund for Compensation (PFC).
</P>
<P>
Under the decision, the price of pastry will rise by 10 to 20
pennies (some 0.9 to 1.8 U.S. cents), the Tunisia Africa News
Agency reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The PFC supervises the distribution of staples whose costs hit
336 million dinars (305.45 million U.S. dollars), accounting for
1.3 percent of the Gross National Product (GNP) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The PFC will continue to provide subsidy to grain products,
edible oil and milk that absorb 95 percent of PFC's expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The prices of subsidized foodstuffs, including grain products,
in Tunisia are the lowest among the Mediterranean basin
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
