<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greeks Urged to Donate Blood for Turkish Quake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Greece's Health Ministry
Wednesday urged citizens to donate blood at state hospitals for
Turkish earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
In an announcement, the ministry said that giving blood would be
the greatest proof of Greek humanitarian feelings towards the
sufferings of their fellow humans in neighboring Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The competent services at hospitals throughout the country had
already been informed about the appeal, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake, measuring 7.0 degrees on the Richter scale, hit
northwestern Turkey early Tuesday and claimed more than 2,000
lives.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Prime Minister Costas Simitis Tuesday sent a telegram
of condolences to his Turkish counterpart, Bulent Ecevit, in which
he expressed Athens' willingness to assist Turkish earthquake
victims.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers with sniffer dogs and heat censors and doctors
with emergency medical supplies Tuesday left for Istanbul, Turkey
on three Greek Air Force C-130 transport planes. Greek
seismologists also had gone to Turkey to consult with their
Turkish counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Greece has promised more help for Turkish earthquake victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
