<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Population Up in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said
population in its 15-member region grew slightly last year to
stand at 375,329,400.
</P>
<P>
The 0.2 percent natural increase was 285,400, considerably less
than net migration of 461,200 in EU's 15 countries, Austria,
Belgium, Britain, Ireland, France, Germany, Italy, Netherlands,
Luxembourg, Finland, Sweden, Denmark, Spain, Portugal and Greece,
EU said in a report published on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"All EU member states witnessed a rise in total population,
except Germany with a 19,400 fall, made up of a 70,200 drop in its
natural increase balanced by 50,800 net migrants," the EU
statistics office, Eurostat, said in the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many central and eastern European countries again saw
population falls, either from natural causes or net migration
outflows. For example, the Ukraine's population fell by 394,300 --
a 300,700 natural decrease with net migration outflow, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
Generally, the whole of 15 EU countries accounted for only 1.0
percent of the world population increase last year. This compares
with 21.7 percent for India and 13.2 percent for China, the
Eurostat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
