<HEADLINE> Kenya: New Finance Minister Appointed to Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's former Energy Minister
Chris Okemo was Wednesday appointed new head of the Finance
Ministry in a bid to pull this east African country out of an
economic morass.
</P>
<P>
Former Finance Minister Francis Masakhalia was transferred to
the Energy Ministry in the swap in a minor cabinet shake-up, which
was ordered by President Daniel arap Moi.
</P>
<P>
Okemo pledged to impose fiscal discipline and curb spending so
as to reverse the current economic decline at a news conference
here shortly after his appointment.
</P>
<P>
"We have to check runaway public expenditure, live within our
means and definitely we will turn the economy around," he said.
</P>
<P>
Okemo, a 52-year-old economist, said that his priority was to
instill discipline by ensuring that the governmental ministries be
kept within their budgets.
</P>
<P>
Any ministry officials found guilty of irregular spending will
be punished, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's economy has been in a recession since 1997 when the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) halted a loan facility in
protest against corruption and poor governance in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Economic growth dropped from 4.6 percent in 1996 to 2.3 percent
in 1997 and 1.8 percent last year. It is predicted to grow at 1.6
percent this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
