<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Seismologists here Wednesday said there is no
connection between the disastrous earthquake in Turkey on Tuesday
and the quake that rocked Cyprus last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A strong aftershock measuring 4.8 degrees on the Richter scale
was felt in Cyprus Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday's quake, measuring 5.8 degrees, caused dozens of
injuries and damaged many buildings, especially in Cyprus'
southern coastal Limassol area where the epicenter was located.
(BC-Cyprus-Turkey-Quake)
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Foreign Ministry on Wednesday "categorically"
denied a newspaper report that its bitter enemy -- the U.S. has sent
a message to Iran via Oman.
</P>
<P>
The official Islamic Republic News Agency reported that an
informed source at the ministry here rejected the report carried
by the English-language daily Tehran Times as "baseless."
</P>
<P>
The newspaper Wednesday quoted an unnamed Foreign Ministry
source as saying "this is the first time Washington sends its
message via Oman, while earlier it used to send all its messages
through Swiss Embassy, which takes care of U.S. interests in Iran.
(BC-Iran-US-Report)
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has sent a delegation to Sudan to help mediate
between the government and opposition groups to end the country's
16-year-old civil war, a national newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Arabic Al-Ahram daily said the Egyptian delegation flew
out of Cairo airport alongside a Libyan delegation to the Sudanese
capital of Khartoum Tuesday night in a joint effort to open
national reconciliation conference between the Sudanese government
and the opposition groups. (BC-Egypt-Libya-Sudan)
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Abdel Fattah Kato, the head of Egypt's Civil Aviation
Authority, on Wednesday denied that it was disrupting flights of
Israeli planes in its airspace.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that a plane of El Al, Israel's national
carrier, flying to Johannesburg, South Africa, Tuesday night was
allowed to fly over Egypt although it did not obtain a permit in
advance. (BC-Egypt-Israel-Flights)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- An Israeli minister Wednesday denied reports that
Prime Minister Ehud Barak had asked U.S. congressmen to stop
pressuring President Bill Clinton to move the U.S. embassy before
the completion of Israeli-Palestinian permanent talks.
</P>
<P>
Haim Ramon, minister at the Prime Minister's Office, told a
special parliamentary session that Barak was misquoted in an
Israel Radio report which said he told visiting U.S. Senator Jim
Bunning and Representative Frank Lobiondo Monday to back down
from pressuring Clinton to move the embassy from Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem. (BC-Israel-Jerusalem) 
</P>
</TEXT>
