<HEADLINE> SADC Pledges Support for Angolan Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Development
Community (SADC) Wednesday pledged its support for the Angolan
government in dealing with the domestic affairs of the war-torn
country.
</P>
<P>
The newly-elected SADC Chairman, Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano made the pledge at a press conference here after the
closing ceremony of the 19th SADC summit in Maputo.
</P>
<P>
Chissano noted that the angolan government has not asked for
arms or troops from the regional organization.
</P>
<P>
But the government of President Jose Eduardo Dos Santos did ask
for moral, political, diplomatic and humanitarian support from the
SADC, Chissano noted.
</P>
<P>
The SADC support is aimed at helping the Angolan government
overcome the difficulties it is facing so that the country can
achieve peace as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian aid will include food and medicine, said the
Mozambican president.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old civil war has plunged the country into dire
difficulties, creating some 200 million refugees. According to
the World Food Program (WFP), Angola need some 13,000 tons of food
aid each month.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Dos Santos said in Maputo Tuesday that his
government will not negotiate with the UNITA rebels led by Jonas
Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his government has always following the
U.N.-brokered 1994 Lusaka peace accord while Savimbi has violated
it by renewing the war.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka peace agreement should be the base of any new peace
initiative for Angola, Dos Santos pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed the possibility of talks with the National Union
for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) at a time when the rebels
are not so strong as it was.
</P>
<P>
The president said that it is the obligation of his government
to defend its people against the rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
