<HEADLINE> SADC Leaders Sign Protocols on Wildlife, Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the 14-member Southern
African Development Community (SADC) Wednesday signed two
protocols on wildlife conservation, law enforcement and health
cooperation, and a declaration on promoting productivity.
</P>
<P>
The leaders signed the documents at a summit here aimed at
resolving regional conflicts and boosting economic development.
</P>
<P>
The protocol on Wildlife conservation and law enforcement is
aimed at establishing within the region and within the framework
of the respective national laws of each member state, common
approaches to the conservation and sustainable use of wildlife
resources and to assist with effective enforcement of the laws
governing those resources.
</P>
<P>
"A protocol on health could not have come at a better time"
when there are so many challenges in health sector in the region,
among which AIDS is on top of the list, a SADC official said.
</P>
<P>
The protocol deals with ways to better use of the health
resources to make a healthier population in the region.
</P>
<P>
A healthy population is critical for sustainable human
development and increased productivity in southern Africa which
continues to have high HIV prevalence rate.
</P>
<P>
The protocol on health encourages cooperation among member
states in addressing health problems and challenges facing them.
</P>
<P>
The declaration on productivity called on member states to
adopt more rational national and regional policies that will
improve productivity so as to make the region more productive and
more competitive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
