<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Online Ad Spending Expected to Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Online advertising is
expected to grow to 11.5 billion U.S. dollars in 2003, surpassing
dollars spent in some traditional media, according to new research
released Wednesday by an Internet commerce research firm.
</P>
<P>
Jupiter Communications said that ad spending will increase 40
percent over the next four years, with financial services,
automotive, and media ventures leading the spending.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier Jupiter report, in 1998, online
advertising increased 34 percent over 1997 to reach 1.92 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Driven by growing online population, the rise in time spent
online, and increasing digital commerce adoption, online
advertising revenues have already surpassed those for outdoor
advertising and will exceed spending for cable advertising and
equal roughly three-quarters of today's radio spending by 2003,
according to Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
Car companies, media firms and financial services companies
will account for nearly half of online ad spending in 2003. But
packaged goods companies, whose ad spending will account for 18
percent of offline dollars, will only contribute seven percent of
online dollars by that time.
</P>
<P>
"Online advertising will serve as a catalyst for change in the
traditional ad business," Jupiter said. "Media integration and the
inevitable erosion of traditional markets will be more important
than the effects of online ad dollar growth."
</P>
<P>
Another U.S. research firm, Forrester Research, estimated last
week that global spending for online advertising will reach 33
billion dollars by 2004, one-third of which will be spent outside
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Forrester projected that U.S. online ad spending will hit 22
billion dollars by 2004. This figure represents 8.1 percent of
projected expenditures for traditional advertising -- exceeding
magazine, yellow pages and radio spending.
</P>
<P>
Over the next five years, the Internet will siphon 27 billion
dollars or 10 percent of all U.S. ad spending -- away from
traditional media, according to Forrester.
</P>
<P>
Outside the United States, online ad spending will increase
from 502 million dollars in 1999 to 10.8 billion dollars in 2004,
capturing 33 percent of global spending, Forrester estimated. In
Europe, online ad will total 5.5 billion dollars in 2004,
representing 5.1 percent of Europe's ad spending. The Asia-Pacific
nations will spend an additional 3.3 billion dollars, or six
percent of traditional ad spending in the region. Latin America
will grow to 1.6 billion dollars in 2004, or 4.8 percent of
regional spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
