<HEADLINE> Romania Ready to Send Aid to Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Romania will soon send more
than 200 military and civilians to Turkey to join the efforts to
search for survivors and put down the quake-caused fire in the
aftermath of a devastating earthquake that rocked western Turkey
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the governmental spokeswoman Adriana Saftoiu, the
Prime Minister Radu Vasile approved on Wednesday a request in this
respect by Turkish Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Romania will send to Turkey a rescue team made of 13 military
and three dogs, two logistic vessels and a tugboat, all manned by
174 troops and destined for fire-fighting and human
transportation.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Romania will send to the scene a fire-fighting
squad composed of 10 utility vans and assisted by 55 military and
civilians. The squad will reach Turkey by ground or be ferried by
a Ro-Ro ship, available at the Ministry of Transport's courtesy.
</P>
<P>
The Tuesday's overnight quake in Turkey measured more than 7 on
the Richter scale and killed nearly 3,500 people.
</P>
<P>
Romania's President Emil Constantinescu on Tuesday expressed
sympathy and solidarity for the the bereaved families and the
Turkish people immediately after hearing the disaster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
