<HEADLINE> Cease-Fire Agreement Holds in Kisangani: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The cease-fire agreement signed
 Tuesday by Rwanda and Uganda to stop fighting in Congo's third
largest city still holds, rebel sources in Kisangani told Rwanda
News Agency (RNA) late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
''The situation is calm, people have vacated to their usual
activities after a night of merriment of jubilation because the
fighting had stopped," said Moise Nyarugabo, Vice President of the
Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD).
</P>
<P>
He said that Rwandan army chief of staff Brigadier General
Kayumba Nyamwasa and his Ugandan counterpart Major General Jeje
Odongo had left Kigali for Kisangani to investigate who first
provoked the battle which raged through Kisangani for four
consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
He said RCD-Goma eagerly awaits for the report of the
verification mission, adding that ousted leader of RCD Ernest
Wamba dia Wamba should be held responsible for the bloodshed that
claimed many lives in the recent fighting in Kisangani, and should
be expelled from the rebel movement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
