<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Health Insurance Company Founded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti Health
Insurance Company (KHIC) was formed on Wednesday in preparation
for the enforcement of a government health insurance program for
the first time in the welfare state.
</P>
<P>
Fahd Al-Rajaan, the director of the Public Authority for
Social Security, said the founding of the KHIC was aimed at easing
the pressure on the state budget while improving health services.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the company would take about a year before
presenting a comprehensive health insurance plan.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti parliament endorsed early this year the
government-proposed Health Insurance Scheme, which encourages the
private sector to participate in the country's health services.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, expatriates, which account for over 60
percent of Kuwait's population, will be obliged to buy health
insurance before they can obtain a resident identification card
or have it extended.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners, along with Kuwaitis, were receiving free medical
services before August 17, when Kuwait began to impose symbolic
charges on expatriates visiting public clinics and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's former Health Minister Dr. Adel Al-Sabih had said
that by implementing the scheme, the government is expected to
receive a revenue of 50 million Kuwaiti dinars (165 million
U.S. dollars) a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
