<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican President Elected SADC Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's President Joaquim
Chissano was elected on Wednesday as the new chairman of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
Chissano takes over from South African President Thabo Mbeki to
lead the 14-member group into the 21rst century.
</P>
<P>
SADC leaders are meeting at a summit to address problems
ranging from political issues and military strifes to economic
development and poverty.
</P>
<P>
The organization, originally known as the Southern African
Development Coordination Conference (SADCC), was formed in Zambian
capital Lusaka on April 1, 1980. On August 17, 1992, the SADCC
member states signed a treaty establishing the Southern African
Development Community, which replaced the SADCC.
</P>
<P>
The treaty places binding obligations on member countries, with
the aim of promoting economic integration toward a fully developed
common market.
</P>
<P>
The community offers trade, industry and investment
opportunities in a regional market of 199 million people with a
gross domestic product of 176
billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
