<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Minister Denies Barak Supports Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 18 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli minister Wednesday
denied reports that Prime Minister Ehud Barak had asked
U.S. congressmen to stop pressuring President Bill Clinton to move
the U.S. embassy before the completion of Israeli-Palestinian
permanent talks.
</P>
<P>
Haim Ramon, minister at the Prime Minister's Office, told a
special parliamentary session that Barak was misquoted in an
Israel Radio report which said he told visiting U.S. Senator Jim
Bunning and Representative Frank Lobiondo Monday to back down
from pressuring Clinton to move the embassy from Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Barak said moving the embassy at the current stage would
incite Palestinian violence, the report said, adding he has also
ordered an investigation over how his words had been leaked out,
Israel Radio said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a fierce debate in the Knesset (Parliament), interim leader
of the right-wing Likud party Ariel Sharon charged that the
report showed Barak was willing to partition Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
A leading pro-Israel lobbyist group in the U.S. has decided
to suspend its effort to lobby for the relocation of the
embassy aimd the news, saying the Congress should not be more
aggressive than an Israeli prime minister on the issue of
Jerusalem, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Israel seized the Arab East Jerusalem from Jordan control
in the 1967 Middle East war and later annexed it, claiming
the whole city as its "undivided and eternal capital."
</P>
<P>
The international community, however, does not recognize
Israel's claim over Jerusalem. Most countries locate their
embassies in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
In October 1995, the U.S. Congress approved a bill requiring
the U.S. embassy to be moved to Jerusalem by May 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has since resisted the pressure by
using waivers the bill granted the president to postpone the move
on grounds of national security.
</P>
<P>
The fate of Jerusalem, together with other sensitive issues
like a possible Palestinian state, is supposed to be discussed
in the final-status talks according to signed Israeli-Palestinian
peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Barak has expressed hope that Israel and the Palestinians would
work out a framework of the final-status talks by February
2000. The talks, however, have yet to begin.
</P>
<P>
Although considered moderate on the Israeli-Arab peace process,
Barak sticks to hard lines on the issue of Jerusalem as
various Israeli governments have done, insisting that Jerusalem
should remain the "capital of Israel" under a permanent peace
treaty with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want East Jerusalem as the capital of an
independent Palestinian state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
