<HEADLINE> Russia Attacks Albanian Extremists for Dishonoring  U.N. Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Russia Wednesday voiced
its concerns over the slow pace in disarming the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA) and said that "the actions of Albanian
extremists challenge the international community and constitute a
gross violation of United Nations Security Council Resolution
1244," which recognizes the U.N. authority and the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The statement, contained in a press release issued here by the
Russian Mission to the United Nations, came as the U.N. Security
Council is meeting in a closed-door session to discuss the Kosovo
issue.
</P>
<P>
"Moscow is concerned about the fact that the process of
disarmament of Kosovo militants is proceeding very slowly," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"There are all grounds to believe that a considerable part of
the arms subject to surrender by the sixtieth day of the
demilitarization (August 10, 1999) will be withheld," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"There is risk that the agreement on the eventual disarmament
of Albanian extremists in Kosovo within the 90-day period will not
be implemented either, while the arms we are talking about are
being actively used by the militants to establish their own order
in that autonomous territory of Yugoslavia," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to the clear demands of the Security Council, there
is continued rampant violence in Kosovo, and a growing number of
killings of civilians, arson, and looting of the property of the
non-Albanian population," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"In effect, 'ethnic cleansing' is in full swing in Kosovo," the
statement said. "This is the result of the 'policy of appeasement'
of Albanian separatism conducted by some Western countries."
</P>
<P>
"We regret to note that the international force deployed in
Kosovo is not coping with the wave of terror that has swept the
territory," the statement said. "We believe that the said Security
Council resolution provides the international force with enough
powers to take more resolute actions to restore order."
</P>
<P>
"It is also necessary to speed up the deployment of the United
Nations mission in Kosovo called upon to ensure civic law and
order and exercise main administrative functions in the territory
in the transitional period," the statement said. "It is also
surprising that the International Tribunal for the Former
Yugoslavia displays such inactivity in respect of the crimes being
perpetrated in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
"The international community should take vigorous measures to
rectify the dangerous trends in the development of the situation
in Kosovo, and bring the process back into the mainstream of
political settlement with full respect for sovereignty and
territorial integrity of Yugoslavia," the statement added.
</P>
</TEXT>
