<HEADLINE> Retail Sales Picking Up But Still Weak in UK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 18 (Xinhua) - Sales on Britain's high streets
are picking up at their fastest rate for 18 months, official
figures released Wednesday showed.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales volumes for the three months to the end of July
increased 1.3 percent on the previous three months, marking the
biggest rise since February 1998, the Office for National
Statistics (INS) said.
</P>
<P>
Economists believe as 1999 has progressed and the predictions
of recession have receded, High Street stores have been tempting
shoppers back by cutting prices in the increasingly competitive
market.
</P>
<P>
A variety of surveys have found that this has begun to
accelerate the increase in consumer spending. But the official ONS
figures suggest that they may have overstated the case.
</P>
<P>
The figures were not seen as strong enough to spark fears that
the economy may be heating up which would increase pressure on the
Bank of England to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Geoffrey Dicks, economist at NatWest Bank, said: "The figures
were pretty weak. We were misled by earlier upbeat surveys from
the likes of the Confederation of British Industry." 
</P>
</TEXT>
