<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction Business Up Slightly in Italy's South, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 18 (Xinhua) -- In a small sign of hope for the
south's troubled economy, construction business rose slightly in
1998, according to a report issued Wednesday by the Bank of Italy.
</P>
<P>
But the positive numbers, mostly in the business of renovation
and reconstruction, were mixed still with troubling signs of the
effects of organized crime and a stagnant economy in the poor
regions throughout the south.
</P>
<P>
The Basilicata, one of the poorest south regions, witnessed a
doubling of bidding for public works contracts from 173 billion
lire (about 96 million U.S. dollars) to 351 billion lire (about
195 million U.S. dollars), while the entire south, including the
islands of Sicily and Sardinia rose 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Still the Bank of Italy report concludes that the signs of
recovery "remain weak nonetheless because of the limited number of
work sites effectively activated and the stagnant state of
residential construction and the modest effects of the fiscal
incentives for renovations."
</P>
<P>
Pointing the finger at the "weight of illegal and criminal
economy," the report estimates that 14 percent of the population
of the region of Campania, whose capital is the famous criminal
city of Naples, live in cities in which organized crime has
infiltrated local governing bodies and business.
</P>
<P>
In the region of Calabria, 1998 marked a growth of 1,000 jobs
in the construction industry over the year before. Puglia, struck
by a stalled home building market, has seen employment drop 4.5
percent in the construction business.
</P>
<P>
Sicily and Sardinia, the report concludes, are still suffering
from economic "stagnation," showing only some improvement in the
renovation sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
