<HEADLINE> Canada-U.S. Report Released to Protect Great Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Canada responded quickly to a
Canada-U.S. water report released Wednesday, saying the country
enjoys support for prohibiting bulk water removals from Canadian
watersheds.
</P>
<P>
In a joint announcement, Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy and Environment Minister David Anderson said they are
pleased to receive the International Joint Commission (IJC)
interim report.
</P>
<P>
The interim report Protection of the Waters of the Great Lakes
"supports the federal approach to protecting all of our waters
against removals," Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
"Canadians expect all governments to work together to protect
our watersheds and ensure the preservation of fresh water
suppliers for future generations," Environment Minister Anderson
stated.
</P>
<P>
Canadian media expected the IJC recommendations to form the
basis of water policy for both Canada and the United States.
</P>
<P>
A growing number of businessmen are attempting to skim billions
of litres of Canada's fresh water and send it to parched areas of
the United States and Asia, according to the media.
</P>
<P>
Some futurists have suggested the wars of the next millenium
will be fought over the dwindling supply of fresh water, the media
said.
</P>
<P>
Canada claims to boast one-fifth of the world's fresh water,
with one-half of that in the Great Lakes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
