<HEADLINE> UNDP Aids Zimbabwe's Environmental Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) provides a fund of 210,000 U.S. dollars to Zimbabwe
for a project to find alternative ozone depletion substances,
according to an agreement signed here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The project would be aimed at finding alternatives of methyl
bromide which affects the ozone, Zimbabwean Permanent Secretary of
the Mines, Environment and Tourism Ministry Charles Chipato said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the implementation of the project would
significantly reduce the use of methyl bromide, which is widely
used in the tobacco industry and farming.
</P>
<P>
Chipato pointed out that as the second largest consumer of
methyl bromide in Africa, Zimbabwe consumes annually about 1,000
tons of methyl bromide, of which 83 percent is used for tobacco
seedbeds, 14 percent for things like grain, and three percent for
other uses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
