<HEADLINE> Ugandan, Rwandan Presidents Arrive to Discuss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Presidents of Uganda and Rwanda
arrived here Wednesday to join southern African leaders at a
summit aimed at promoting peace and economic development in the
region.
</P>
<P>
An official at the Mozambican Prime Minister's Press Office
said the two leaders "are already here". As he spoke, the Ugandan
president was seen entering the conference room.
</P>
<P>
Jerode Nbondasi, foreign minister of the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC), welcomed their arrival, saying that "it is a good
thing for them to come here directly".
</P>
<P>
"We are waiting for them," he told reporters during a luncheon
break. He reiterated the demand that Ugandan and Rwandan troops
withdraw from the DRC. "They ought to go home," he said, while
accusing the two countries of " unfaithfully" breaching peace
accords.
</P>
<P>
Nbondasi earlier categorically refused to talk with any Ugandan
and Rwandan delegations that might arrive here.
</P>
<P>
Nbondasi is representing DRC President Laurent Kabila at
Wednesday summit of the Southern African Development Community
(SADC).
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda support different factions fighting in the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) by dispatching troops to
the war-torn country. The Ugandan and Rwandan troops based in the
DRC fought each other on August 15.
</P>
<P>
Uganda President Yoweri Museveni and Rwandan Vice President and
Minister of Defense Paul Kagame agreed to a cease-fire between
their troops on Tuesday after marathon talks.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders reaffirmed their commitment to cooperating with
the verification teams from Zambia and South Africa and seeking a
peaceful resolution of the conflict in the DRC on the basis of the
Lusaka ceasefire accord signed on July 10 by six relevant states.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda are not SADC members. Their participation in
the SADC summit would show the two countries' willingness to end
fighting in the DRC, a SADC official said.
</P>
<P>
The summit was running badly behind schedule. It was supposed
to start behind closed doors at 09:00 Wednesday, but two hours
later the proceedings had not yet begun.
</P>
<P>
Kabila originally intended to head the DRC delegation, and even
flew into Maputo on Monday. But he left abruptly for home on
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The explanation offered by host president Joaquim Chissano for
Kabila's departure was the deteriorating situation in the DRC.
</P>
</TEXT>
