<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Talks on Prisoner Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
negotiations centering on the issue of Palestinian prisoners
broke down Wednesday evening, with the two sides disputing over
how many security prisoners jailed for anti-Israel activities
should be released.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's envoy Gilad Sher told chief
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat in the talks that Israel would
not change its criterion for the release of prisoners at this
stage, but would review the issue in individual bases in the
future, according to a statement issued by the Prime Minister's
Office after the talks.
</P>
<P>
Sher also reiterated that the verbal agreement over the
prisoner issue reached at the sideline of the Wye accord last
October did not differentiate between common criminals and
security prisoners, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
In their previous talks Tuesday night, the negotiators agreed
to draw up a list of 650 Palestinian prisoners for review. A joint
committee convening Wednesday did not make breakthrough after
examining the list for five hours.
</P>
<P>
No new date has been set for further negotiations, according
to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Erekat has said that he expected Israel to release the 650
security prisoners before implementation of the Wye accord begins
on September 1.
</P>
<P>
But an Israeli official involved in the talks told Israel
Radio Wednesday that Israel could only free up to 250 Palestinian
security prisoners and they would be released in two dispatches,
in September and October respectively, rather than before
September.
</P>
<P>
Under the Wye accord, Israel is obligated to release 750
Palestinian prisoners in three stages. Former prime minister
Benjamin Netanyahu ordered the release of 250 prisoners last
November, but most of the released were common criminals instead
of security prisoners the Palestinian National Authority had
required.
</P>
<P>
The dispute sparked weeks of bloodiest violence in years
between Palestinians and Israeli soldiers in the West Bank and
Gaza.
</P>
<P>
There were signs that the new moderate government of Barak
might ease the criteria for the release of security prisoners,
but it has rejected Palestinian stance that only security
prisoners should be released.
</P>
<P>
Haim Ramon, minister without portfolio in the prime minister's
office, denied reports in a parliamentary debate Wednesday that
Barak would agree to release prisoners with "blood on their
hands," referring to those participating in serious anti-Israel
attacks.
</P>
<P>
He told Israel Radio earlier that even if the criterion were
stretched, only 250 security prisoners could be released, not 650
as the Palestinians have demanded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
