<HEADLINE> Ghana to Save $400M Through Energy Efficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Ghana can save more than 400
million U.S. dollars and reduce carbon emissions by 230,000 tons
by the year 2010 on refrigerators if energy conservation measures
are strictly adhered to, the Ghana News Agency (GNA) reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A survey by five energy-related institutions found that
another eight million dollars could be saved from the consumption
of room air conditioners with a carbon emission reduction of
38,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The savings represent a 10 percent cut in energy consumption,
Minister of Mines and Energy Fred Ohene Kena said Wednesday at the
launch of "Energy Wise", a brochure published by the Energy
Foundation to guide consumers on efficient practices in Accra,
capital of the west African country.
</P>
<P>
The survey was conducted by the Energy Foundation in
collaboration with the Alliance to Save Energy, United States
Agency for International Development (USAID), Lawrence Berkeley
National Laboratory and the Ministry of Mines and Energy.
</P>
<P>
 Kena said that appropriate steps are being taken to enact
laws to ensure that energy resources are optimally utilized.
</P>
<P>
 Other measures will be to support the Energy Foundation and
the Ghana Standards Board to come out with minimum energy
efficiency standards and labels for domestic energy consuming
appliances and industrial electric motors.
</P>
<P>
 He said some industries are losing in highly competitive
international markets due to the use of inefficient technologies.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
