<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Criticizes India's Drafted Nuclear Doctrine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
Wednesday that India's draft nuclear doctrine was designed to
build a nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
"We find it a document that describes the desire to develop a
nuclear arsenal and that is something that we think is not in the
security interests of India, the subcontinent or the United States
or the world," State Department spokesman James Rubin said at a
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"We don't find it an encouraging document," he added.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time that Washington criticized India's
nuclear doctrine, which, drafted by the government-appointed
national Security Advisory Board, proposes a nuclear deterrent
based on aircraft, ships and mobile land-based missiles.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Rubin said the United States opposed India's
drafted nuclear doctrine because it was "moving in the wrong
direction."
</P>
<P>
He said the move could only create "an action-reaction cycle
that will increase the risks" to the subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
Washington has consistently urged India and Pakistan, which
both carried out nuclear tests last year, to refrain from
developing nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Washington would continue to urge both states to
sign and ratify the nuclear Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration also wanted them "to not weaponize
missiles so that they can carry nuclear weapons, to stop the
production of fissile material, and to develop an export control
system," Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
