<HEADLINE> SADC Reiterates Call for Political Solution to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) ended their summit here Wednesday
after adopting a communique calling for political solutions to
regional conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The communique, read by SADC executive secretary Kaire Mbuende,
 expressed concern at the setbacks reflected in the emergence of
unrest and conflict in Angola and the Democratic Republic of
Congo.
</P>
<P>
"The situation in Lesotho and the recent armed confrontation in
the Caprivi region of Namibia are equally sources of serious
concern," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said the SADC stands for efforts to seek a diplomatic and
political solution to the Angolan conflict, while reiterating
support for the Angolan government.
</P>
<P>
"The summit expressed solidarity with the Angolan people in
their efforts to strengthen the democratic authority of the state
through the establishment of peace through political and
diplomatic means," it said.
</P>
<P>
The document said the SADC has entrusted SADC newly-elected
chairman Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano and South African
President Thabo Mbeki to mediate the Angolan conflict.
</P>
<P>
The SADC leaders, in the statement, also renewed their
commitment to peace efforts in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
"Concerning the Congo, the summit expressed satisfaction over
the initiatives launched to bring peace to the Country," the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
The SADC has undertaken measures to ensure that Congolese
rebels sign the cease-fire agreement, which would pave the way for
the withdrawal of foreign forces from the Congo, it said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the governments of Uganda and Rwanda reaffirmed
their commitment to the peaceful resolution of the conflict in the
Congo and to the swift implementation of the Lusaka agreement
signed on July 10.
</P>
<P>
On the recent developments in Namibia, the summit "strongly and
 unreservedly condemned the secessionist attack on Katima Mulilo
in the Caprivi region, and reaffirmed the inviolability of the
territorial integrity of Namibia," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The summit indicated its full support of the actions taken by
the government of Namibia to return the situation to normality,"
it noted.
</P>
<P>
It said the summit called upon the government and the people of
Lesotho to continue to use open dialogue and consultations in
order to deepen the democratic process which would facilitate the
holding of fresh elections in Lesotho. 
</P>
</TEXT>
