<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Reports Inadequate World Response to Somali Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Wednesday said that despite the persistent security
threats and rising distribution costs caused by clan conflicts,
mines and other problems, U.N. agencies and their humanitarian
partners continue to deliver food aid to a high proportion of the
most affected areas, and to most settlements known to have
incorporated families.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report on the situation in Somalia, Annan said,
"The operational capacity of humanitarian agencies has gradually
been eroded, primarily owing to inadequate donor support for
medium-term rehabilitation measures."
</P>
<P>
"For United Nations agencies, this is shown by the weak donor
response to the 1999 Consolidated Appeal, which was severely
prioritized and focused in response to donor wishes," Annan said
in the report, presented to the U.N. Security Council Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, the capacity of the agencies to provide
efficient, effective humanitarian relief has been weakened, making
response to future crises ever more difficult," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, inadequate medium-term funding reduces the ability
of humanitarian agencies to provide crucial, if more mundane,
activities related to disaster prevention and the building of
social resilience," he said.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has been in conflict since the 1991 ouster of the late
leader Mohamed Siad Barre by a coalition of rebels.
</P>
<P>
After Siad Barre's ouster, the rebels turned against each
other, and the country disintegrated into fiefdoms protected by
clan-based militias. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Baby Deaths Continue to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Infant mortality continues to
fall throughout Europe with a rate of fewer than five deaths of
babies under one year per 1,000 live births last year in Germany,
France, Austria, Finland, Sweden, Iceland, Norway and Switzerland,
the European Union (EU) said in a report published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 15-country EU's average of infant mortality is 5.2 compared
to 4.1 in Japan, 6.4 in the United States, 63.1 in India and 45.5
in China, the EU statistics office, Eurostat, said in the report.
The EU's figure in 1980 stood at 12.4, it added.
</P>
<P>
The "safest place" for a baby to be born is Sweden with the
death rate of only 3.5, while the longest living in the EU are
French baby girls (82.2-year-old), the report noted.
</P>
<P>
The report predicted that EU babies born in 1998 can expect to
live 80.8 years if they are girls and 74.5 if they are boys.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the average EU woman has 1.45 children with the high
of 1.94 in Ireland and the low of 1.15 in Spain. These figures
compare with 2.07 in the United States, 1.8 in China and 3.24 in
India, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, births outside marriage continue to rise everywhere in
Europe, the report said. "These amounted to one in every two
births in Sweden, Estonia and Norway and two out of three in
Iceland." In the European Union region, it is about one in four,
though nearly one in five in the 11-member euro-zone, Eurostat
said, adding that the trend "reflects the growing popularity of
cohabitation and a decline in the incidence of marriage."
</P>
<P>
Eurostat also underlined the declining popularity of marriage
and the rise in divorces in the EU. "The crude marriage rate in
1998 was five per 1,000 population compared to 6.3 in 1980. The
range last year was from 3.6 in Sweden to 6.7 in Portugal," it
said.
</P>
<P>
EU divorces are running at a crude rate of around 1.8 per 1,000
population with a high of 2.7 in Finland, the report added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Students to Join in Picking Cloves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The government of Zanzibar
will close all government-run primary and secondary public schools
for a month as from next Monday to enable students and teachers to
participate in clove picking exercise.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference in Zanzibar Wednesday, Principal
Secretary in the isles' Ministry of Education Abdulhamid Mzee said
the move is aimed at salvaging the prime cash crop, which
contributes more than 44 percent to local gross domestic product
(GDP).
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibari government foresees a bumper harvest of 10,000
tons this season, reports reaching here quoted the permanent
secretary as saying. Mzee said the decision to close schools has
been reached following complaints from growers and parents that
the work force to harvest cloves is far from enough and there is a
danger that some of the cloves could get spoilt.
</P>
<P>
He also observed that most of the public schools in Pemba
Island, where 80 percent of Zanzibar's cloves are grown, have been
recording "poor attendance" since the picking exercise started
last month.
</P>
<P>
He added that teachers were also allowed to take up unpaid
leave in a bid to participate in clove picking exercise.
</P>
<P>
The compulsory closure of schools will end on September 20,
according to Mzee.
</P>
<P>
The principal secretary said private schools are free to make
choice on whether or not to close.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the government raised producer prices for cloves in
renewed efforts to encourage growers to harvest the spice and
recover costs.
</P>
<P>
A kilogram of first grade clove fetches 600 shillings (about 75
U.S. cents) instead of 450 shillings. The second grade rises to
550 shillings from 400 shillings. The third grade is 500 shillings
instead of 350 shillings and the fourth grade is 300 shillings
instead of 250 shillings.
</P>
<P>
Cloves are also grown in Indonesia, Brazil and the Indian Ocean
islands of Comoros, Mauritius and Madagascar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0051 </DOCNO>
