<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W. African Leaders Urged to Pursue Stability, Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President's
representative and officials of the Economic Community of the West
Africa States (ECOWAS) Wednesday urged leaders of the west
African sub-region to help sustain the burgeoning democracy and
step up economic integration.
</P>
<P>
"This sub-region has had enough of military rule. We need
economic and political stability in order to attain the goals of
economic integration at a time when we are entering a new
millennium," Obasanjo, through his chief economic adviser, told
the opening session of the 44th Ministerial Council of the
16-nation regional organization in Nigeria's capital Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Philip Asiodu, representing Nigeria's president said the
sub-region should work toward the elimination of all contentious
issues which may give causes for military incursion into civil
governance.
</P>
<P>
The president adviser lamented that the sub-region continue to
find itself marginalized when the gap between it and the rest of
the world is actually getting wider.
</P>
<P>
Citing the 1999 world development report, he said all but two
of the 16 member countries in the sub-region are among the poorest
34 countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
West Africa cannot stagnate when others were developing, said
Nigeria's president through his aide, adding that the three-day
council meeting should come up with far-reaching proposals for the
October ECOWAS summit.
</P>
<P>
Lack of policy harmonization is undermining the integration
process of the region, said the ECOWAS Executive Secretary lansana
kouyate at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the ECOWAS's progress was hindered by delays
in the implementation of customs union program, trade
liberalization scheme and common external tariff.
</P>
<P>
The delays have impeded free movement of people and goods
across the region, said the Executive Secretary.
</P>
<P>
It is a shame that there are still as many as 174 road blocks
for extortion along the international highways linking the
Lagos-Cotonou-Lome- Accra-Abidjan-Ouagadougou-Lome hub, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Council Chairman, Togolese Economic and Finance Minister
Abdoul- Hamid Dourodjaye said in his speech that steps should be
fastened in achieving the macro-economic convergence and creation
of a single monetary zone.
</P>
<P>
To achieve this objective, Dourodjaye said ECOWAS member states
must ensure political stability by putting an end to coups, social
upheavals and armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The minister's meeting is responsible for, among other things,
the restructuring of the organization's Abuja-based secretariat
and its Lome- based ECOWAS fund. A communique is expected at the
end of the meeting on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
