<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-18 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Istanbul Residents Facing Aftermath of Quake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, August 18 (Xinhua) -- A group of women, wearing
headscarves, squated on the ground beside the debris of a toppled
six-floor building in Aucilar, Istanbul late Wednesday night,
praying for the three children being rescued by relief workers
from under the concrete.
</P>
<P>
It is still not known whether the three children are alive or
not as the three children have been trapped since the powerful
earthquake struck the area in the early hours of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
One of the women, surnamed Aycer, told Xinhua that the
building collapsed instantly as the quake occurred. Seven bodies
have already been recovered from under the tangled steel and
concrete.
</P>
<P>
"God bless the children trapped in the building," Aycer
said. However, rescue workers conceded that the chance of
survival for the children seemed slim.
</P>
<P>
Aucilar, a scenic district in western Istanbul overseeing the
Marmara Sea, was the most seriously hit part in Istanbul,
the largest city of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
At least 100 people have been killed and 700 others injured in
Aucilar alone, as the fatalities in Istanbul, with a population of
12 million, were so far put at 290.
</P>
<P>
From under a crushed 10-floor house, the tallest building
reduced to rubbles in Aucilar in the quake, rescuers pulled out
25 people, injured but alive.
</P>
<P>
Another seven people were still trapped inside, survivors
said. Rescuers doubted they could pull them out.
</P>
<P>
Rescue experts warned people against moving into the
buildings.
</P>
<P>
Makeshift shelters can be seen at almost any open field in
Aucilar, like in other part of Istanbul as residents fled their
home to camp outside for fear of major aftershocks.
</P>
<P>
Over 3,000 people have been confirmed dead and over 10,000
injured in the disastrous quake, measuring 7.4 degrees on
the Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
The death toll is certainly to climb as another 10,000 people
are still buried under the flattened buildings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
