<HEADLINE> U.S. Welcomes DPRK Statement on Missile Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The United States Wednesday
made a response to a statement on the missile program by the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), seeing it as a
"window of opportunity" for better relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
DPRK party secretary Kim Yong-sun told CNN in an interview this
week that Pyongyang was considering a less volatile missile
policy, but warned that if his country detected aggression against
it, it would retaliate.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the DPRK's Foreign Ministry said his country
was ready to discuss its missile program with other nations. Other
nations must however prove that they were not a threat to
Pyongyang, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the statement, the U.S. State Department said
Washington saw "a window of opportunity" for improving its
relations with the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
"We think that there is a window of opportunity, and we
certainly hope that North Korea seizes that opportunity,"
spokesman James Rubin said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
He said better relations could mean normalization of relations,
liaison offices, diplomatic representation and eliminating or
limiting economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The United States and the DPRK have held bilateral talks on
the DPRK's missile program since 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
