<HEADLINE> EU Shares 6.3 Percent of World Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said
Wednesday that all its people of 15 countries share 6.3 percent of
the world's population, with the figure of 375,329,400 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The other European countries accounted for 7.3 percent of the
total world population of 6 billion, the EU statistics office,
Eurostat, said in a report published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Eurostat also cited the data provided by the International
Program Center of the U.S. Bureau of Census, indicating that China
takes the lion's share of 20.8 percent of the world's population,
followed by India with 16.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
So far, the United States, Japan and other more developed
countries account for 7.6 percent of the world's population while
the world's less developed countries hold 41.3 percent with a rate
of 60.1 percent of population increase in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
