<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Job Insecurity Highest Among Professionals in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Professionals have overtaken
manual workers as the most insecure group within the workforce in
Britain, new research showed.
</P>
<P>
A study, conducted by researchers at Cambridge University,
found that despite the economic recovery and low unemployment, the
middle class are growing more fearful of redundancy, the Times
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Job insecurity among professionals has risen 28 percent since
1986, according to an index devised by the researchers that sets
people's fear of becoming unemployed against their perception of
how likely it is to happen.
</P>
<P>
On the same scale, manual workers showed a slight decrease in
job insecurity.
</P>
<P>
One of the study's most striking findings is the degree to
which job insecurity has united employees of all ranks and set
them solidly against their bosses.
</P>
<P>
The survey used government data on 5,500 adults and surveyed
300 men and women.
</P>
<P>
The study found that while many professionals were not afraid
of losing their job, they were very worried about the potential
loss of valued job features, such as their status within their
company and their opportunity for promotion.
</P>
<P>
Two thirds of people surveyed said they regularly worked longer
than their basic working hours and 39 percent said that working
hours had increased over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent said the speed of work and the effort they
put into their job had increased over the past five years. But far
from motivating employees to try harder in order to ensure they
were not sacked, this merely served to demotivate most
respondents.
</P>
<P>
The study concluded that short-term improvements in efficiency
are being achieved at the cost of long-term ill-health and
destruction of the social environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatian FM Arrives in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Croatian Deputy Prime Minister
and Foreign Minister Mate Granic arrived here Wednesday to start
his visit to Albania.
</P>
<P>
Albanian President Rexhep Meidani, Prime Minister Pandeli Majko
and Foreign Minister Paskal Milo met with Granic Wednesday
respectively, stressing that the two countries should strengthen
their bilateral ties, especially in the field of trade.
</P>
<P>
Meidani said that Albania and Croatia should increase their
economic and human contacts, and build an air or sea corridor for
that purpose with the liberalization of visas between the two
countries, according to the Albanian Telegraphic Agency.
</P>
<P>
Granic agreed to Meidani's ideas on stronger ties between the
two countries, saying that his current visit to Albania is aimed
at evaluating the prospect for the cooperation between the two
countries in compliance with the Stability Pact for Southeastern
Europe signed in July in Sarajevo, capital of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Majko expressed, during his meeting with Granic, thanks for
Groatia's assistance to Albania during the Kosovo crisis, saying
that Croatia is an important partner of Albania.
</P>
<P>
Majko also expressed his hope that a tripartite meeting of
representatives of Albania, Croatia and Montenegro could be held.
</P>
<P>
Granic said that Croatia wishes to intensify its ties with
Albania, while indicating Croatia is interested in having good
ties with all the countries of the region.
</P>
<P>
Milo confirmed the Albanian government's desire for stronger
ties with Croatia during his meeting with Granic. The two also
discussed the current situation in Kosovo and agreed that
cooperation is needed to stabilize the situation there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Gold Production to Remain Flat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 18 (Xinhua) -- World gold production is
expected to remain flat through the next four years, the Gold
Institute reported Wednesday in its annual forecast of world gold
mine production.
</P>
<P>
Trends in declining exploration expenditure and the closure of
high cost mines are beginning to lower projections for future gold
production, said the international industry association in a
report.
</P>
<P>
World gold mine production grew 3 percent in 1998 to reach 82
million ounces, despite gold prices that averaged 37 U.S. dollars
per ounce less than those in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Gold Institute's new forecast for 2002, at 83 million
ounces, shows 1 percent growth from 1998. However, the report
said, those projections were made when gold was at 285 dollars per
ounce. It is likely that if the current 255-dollar price had been
taken into consideration, some forecasts would have been lower.
Unless prices recover, instead of growing 1 percent, it is more
likely that production will decline 1.5 percent to 2 percent per
year for the next few years.
</P>
<P>
On a regional basis, the report said that the trends identified
last year are continuing. Twelve percent growth in Latin America
and 7 percent in Asia are offset by declines of 11 percent in
Oceania and 7 percent in North America.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, the world's largest gold producer, produced 15
million ounces in 1998, down 5 percent from 1997. If production
continues to decline at the rate it has for the past five year,
the report said, South Africa will produce only a little over 12
million ounces in 2002.
</P>
<P>
U.S. production is expected to decline 6 percent to just over
11 million ounces in 2002.
</P>
<P>
A reduction totaling 1.2 million ounces or 12 percent is
expected to bring production in Australia down to 8.8 million
ounces in 2002.
</P>
<P>
In Canada, gold production of 5.3 million ounces in 1998 is
forecast to decline to 4.8 million ounces in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has experienced tremendous growth since 1990, and is
expected to overtake both China and Canada in the next three years
with projected growth of 11 percent to 5.2 million ounces in 2002.
</P>
<P>
The Gold Institute compiled the study with the participation of
more than 100 mining entities from 70 countries supplying actual
production data and projections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
