<HEADLINE> World Bank Promises to Help Turkey Reconstruct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- World Bank President James D.
Wolfensohn Wednesday expressed his deep sympathy to the government
and people of Turkey after the massive earthquake that struck
Monday, and promised to reallocate substantial funds and mobilize
further assistance to help the country.
</P>
<P>
"Within 36 hours of the earthquake, we reallocated around 100
million U.S. dollars out of existing loans and have already
identified another 120 million dollars in new loans to be
available for reconstruction needs," Wolfensohn said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"With our government counterparts, we have begun rapid work to
assess all those needs and the associated costs, and together we
will design smooth mechanisms for getting the necessary funding to
most vital rebuilding and future human needs," he added.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has helped with the recovery from past natural
disasters in Turkey -- including the Erzincan and Adana
earthquakes -- and is committed to helping the country with
reconstruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
