<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Move Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks moved lower
Wednesday as investors were waiting for a decision by the Federal
Reserve on the possibility of higher interest rates to preempt
inflation from the U.S. economy next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 125.70 at
10,991.38 for profit taking after the blue chip index rose 461
points in the five previous sessions.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 11.32 at 1,332.84 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq index fell 13.49 at 2,657.73.
</P>
<P>
Investors' concerns about higher interest rates have hit the
market, dragging the stock indexes well below their closing
records set on July 16. But most indexes rebounded in the past few
days as investors absorbed the possibility of higher rates in
belief that the Federal Reserve would take a moderate action.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe the market may not be able to sustain any new
rallies until after August 24, when the Federal Reserve announces
its decision on the rates.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 5.06 at 623.65 and the Russell
2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.90 at 433.10. But the
American Stock Exchange index rose 1.41 at 783.92.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,801 down, 1,196 up and 539
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 676.73 million shares from 689.89
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
