<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Reaffirm Their Support to Osama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 19 (Xinhua) -- On the eve of the First
anniversary of the U.S. missile attack against Afghanistan, the
ruling Taliban Thursday reiterated that they will not hand over
the alleged terrorist Osama bin Laden to the United Stated, news
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Accusing the United States of conducting international
terrorism, Mulla Mohammad Rabbani, the second senior Taliban
leader, said that the United States was using the Osama issue as a
means to pressure the Taliban regime to yield to U.S. demands.
</P>
<P>
"Osama is our guest and it is the custom of Afghans and Muslims
to respect and care for the guest," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States accused Osama of masterminding the bomb
blasts in U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania last August and
repeatedly demanded the Taliban extradite the Saudi dissident.
</P>
<P>
It attacked the claimed bases of Osama in Afghanistan and Sudan
with cruise missiles on August 20 last year and imposed economic
sanctions on the Taliban this July.
</P>
<P>
"America itself conducts acts of global terrorism by launching
missile attacks against Afghanistan and Sudan. Who is going to
compensate for this?" Rabbani questioned.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban leader vowed that Osama was not allowed to
use Afghanistan to launch activities against other countries and
called for a negotiated settlement of the issue concerning him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Futures Trading Allowed in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government Thursday
issued a notification allowing the Reserve Bank of India and its
authorized banks to deal in futures trading of gold within the
country.
</P>
<P>
This paved the way for activating the Gold Deposit Scheme,
which had been planned for years in India.
</P>
<P>
The Gold Deposit Scheme also envisages exemption of interest on
the gold deposit bonds from income tax and the value of assets
deposited in the scheme from wealth tax.
</P>
<P>
Any capital gains made on these bonds through trading or at
redemption would be eligible for exemption from capital gains tax.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, the minimum gold deposit would be 500 grams
and further deposits would be in multiples of 50 grams.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the process of putting in place the
guidelines and required logistics could take at least six months.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
