<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Standardize Construction Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Minister of Construction Yu
Zhengsheng said here today that 85 percent of the prefecture-level
cities in China have set up trading centers for opening bidding
on construction projects.
</P>
<P>
The trading centers are aimed at ensuring fair and open
competition between contractors, which could resulted in effective
and clean operations in this field, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the government has stepped up its efforts to
battle corruption in the construction sector by encouraging open
bids to avoid under-the-table activities.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, 37,519 projects were contracted,
of which 97.83 percent were contracted through opening bidding,
according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
Minister Yu said that by October 1, all prefecture-level cities
will have their own construction-project trading centers. He
disclosed that related departments are working hard to create the
country's first laws on tendering and bidding.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Supervision He Yong told Xinhua that the number of
corruption cases involving the construction industry continues to
decline. In 1995, authorities uncovered 4,076 such cases, compared
with 1,052 in 1998, and 270 in the first half of this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
