<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 1,000 Foreigners Join in Rescue Work in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, August 19 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 foreign
rescuers and medical workers have joined in massive search and
rescue efforts in northwestern Turkey in the aftermath of
Tuesday's strong earthquake.
</P>
<P>
Despite logistical problems and poor coordination from Turkish
authorities, foreign assistance accelerated the rescue works,
Turkish press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the foreign units were in possession of sniffer dogs
trained to locate living people trapped inside the rubble.
</P>
<P>
The largest foreign assistance team was sent by Israel,
Turkey's close ally in the region. A 200-member team of military
rescuers and medical experts arrived in Turkey on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Greece, Turkey's long-time rival, also sent a 40-member team
to the scene.
</P>
<P>
Other countries that have sent rescue and medical teams
include Russia, Austria, Germany, Bulgaria, Britain, Azerbaijan,
Sweden, Hungary, Belgium, Denmark, Italy, Japan, Georgia and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
A team of Czech rescue workers are expected to arrive on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Humanitarian contributions are also continuing flowing to the
quake-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
Germany has dispatched 1 million Deutch marks (500,000
U.S. dollars) on Tuesday to Turkey. The European Union also
announced to grant 2 million euros (2.1 million dollars) as its
first package of humanitarian aid to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Japan provided 300,000 dollars in aid on Wednesday. The
U.S. pledged financial support for reconstruction. The
U.S. Embassy in Ankara has already released an initial fund of
25,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan has called for
"relief and rehabilitation" fund for the area. The International
Red Cross in Geneva has launched an appeal for some 6.92 million
dollars to aid the quake victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
