<HEADLINE> German Sentenced in Israel for Aiding Militant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 19 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli court Thursday
sentenced a German citizen to 10 years in jail for aiding
the militant group Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
The judges of Tel Aviv District Court said that the
sentence would prevent the similar cases from happening in the
future.
</P>
<P>
Stephan Smyrek, 26, was arrested in November 1997 when he
arrived in Israel. The court was told that he had taken part in a
training course with Hezbollah in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Smyrek was convicted early this week by the court of
aiding Hezbollah, being a member of it and trying to pass
information to it.
</P>
<P>
But the court dismissed allegations by Israel's General
Security Service that Smyrek was planning to carry out a
suicide bomb attack in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Avigdor Feldman, Smyrek's lawyer, had said that Smyrek came to
Israel only to take picture of Israeli public place and send them
to Hezbollah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
