<HEADLINE> Two Men Rewarded for Capturing Fugitive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua)-- Chinese police have rewarded two
ordinary citizens who helped them capture a fugitive homicide
suspect, the Ministry of Public Security said here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yongqiang, public security bureau director of the city of
Shenzhen in south China, awarded 10,000 yuan, equivalent to twice
the average annual income of a Chinese citizen, to Ao Longhua and
Deng Shibibg, two grass-growing company employees, yesterday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time a public security bureau gave such
large reward to citizens who voluntarily helped catch a major
fugitive since the ongoing nationwide campaign against fugitives
began on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Ao and Deng caught Yang Guangming on April 4 as he was stealing
a roadlamp of an overpass. Police interrogated Yang, and found his
personal data in the National Fugitive Information Network, which
was established by the Ministry of Public Security.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, Yang broke into a house and
committed homicide in Shaowu County in east China's Fujian
Province on July 21, before he became a fugitive.
</P>
<P>
Yang had been listed among the 1,000 most-wanted fugitives in
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that since July 1, more than 60,000 fugitives
have been caught nationwide, including 183 of the most-wanted ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
