<HEADLINE> Zambia Needs Capital Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Zambian government has stressed
the need for the capital market to offer innovative investment
opportunities if it has to become meaningful to the private sector
and ordinary Zambians.
</P>
<P>
Katele Kalumba, minister of Finance and Economic Development,
said that more Zambians should be given a chance to participate in
the capital market.
</P>
<P>
He said this when he opened the first national workshop on
collective investment schemes here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that LUSE would fail to live up to its aspirations as a
national stock exchange if its services were not made widely
available.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Swedish ambassador to Zambia Kristina Svensson noted
that very few companies were listed on LUSE to date and that their
turn-over was still low.
</P>
<P>
Svensson said this could only be redressed if LUSE increased
participation and the supply of shares offered on the market.
</P>
<P>
To increase participation of more companies in the financial
market was necessary in order to raise liquidity levels and hence
reduce vulnerability to external stocks, she said.
</P>
<P>
Lack of knowledge about the importance of a capital market had
limited the number of Zambians participating in the market, she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
