<HEADLINE> Indian Rupee Faces Renewed Pressure From U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Indian rupee is facing
renewed pressure from the U.S. currency owing to fresh corporate
dollar demand and short-covering by banks in fairly active trade
at the Interbank Foreign Exchange (FOREX) market in Mumbai
(Bombay) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Indian unit closed at 43.48/49 rupees per dollar, a sharp
six paise decline from overnight closing level of 43.42/43 after
trading in a range of 43.44 rupees and 43.49 rupees.
</P>
<P>
Dollar short-covering by banks on expectation of increased
demand for the U.S. unit from corporates because month-end
considerations exerted fresh pressure on the rupee.
</P>
<P>
Traders said that the State Bank of India was mildly bidding
the dollar, but most of the buying inquiry for the greenback came
from foreign banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
