<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Soars to Monthly Record in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. trade deficit soared to
an all-time monthly high in June because the recorded imports
overwhelmed a modest increase in exports, the Commerce Department
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Department reported that the trade deficit jumped to 24.6
billion dollars in June, a 16.3 percent increase from the 21.2
billion dollars deficit in May.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, imports of goods and services rose a
solid 3.9 percent in June to a record 103 billion dollars while
exports managed a 0.5 percent gain to 78.3 billion dollars, only
the second increase this year.
</P>
<P>
So in the first half of this year, the U.S. trade deficit was
running at an annual rate of 236 billion dollars, 44 percent above
last year's 164.3 billion dollars, which had been a record high.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. trade deficit set records in five of the last six
months. The manufacturers and farmers are struggling to cope with
the loss of markets caused by the world financial crisis while the
consumers, bolstered by the lowest unemployment levels in three
decades, have been snapping up foreign products.
</P>
<P>
The big jump in June's deficit caught analysts by surprise.
Many had been forecasting a slight narrowing on the belief that
U.S. exporters were finally seeing some improvement as Asian
economies began to recover from steep recessions.
</P>
<P>
The deterioration in U.S. trade deficit last month reflected
widening trade gaps with most of the world.
</P>
<P>
U.S. politically sensitive deficit with Japan soared by 19.3
percent in June to 6.3 billion dollars for the month.
</P>
<P>
The deficit with Mexico, one of the U.S. partners in the North
American Free Trade Agreement, swelled 9.4 percent in June to 2.5
billion dollars as imports from that country climbed to an
all-time high.
</P>
<P>
U.S. deficit with West Europe jumped 39 percent to 4.9 billion
dollars as imports from that region also set a record high.
</P>
<P>
The report showed the 3.9 percent increase in imports was led
by a jump of 874 million dollars in shipments of foreign cars and
parts. Other big gains were registered by clothing, which climbed
by 282 million dollars; computers up 422 million dollars; and
telecommunications equipment, up 254 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
U.S. foreign oil bill increased 3.7 percent in June to 5.5
billion dollars as crude oil imports climbed to the highest level
since November 1997.
</P>
<P>
June's report also showed the the rise in exports was led by a
424 million dollars jump in sales of U.S. autos and parts, which
climbed to 6.5 billion dollars, their highest level since July
1977.
</P>
<P>
Sales of U.S. farm products, led by gains in corn and beef
sales, were up 135 million to 3.9 billion dollars, but for the
year were still 7 percent behind 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
