<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Hints not to Sign CTBT by September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Thursday said the
question of its signing the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT)
remains open.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif had promised to sign the
CTBT by September this year "in an atmosphere free of coercion"
last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad told a briefing here
that India's nuclear doctrine it recently raised is serious enough
to make it unavoidable for Islamabad to keep the question of
signing the CTBT open.
</P>
<P>
"We will, of course, be forced to take a final decision (with
regard to CTBT) keeping in view what is happening in our
neighborhood," he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretary said that Pakistan has been closely
monitoring the situation "because we had undertaken to sign the
CTBT in an atmosphere free of coercion."
</P>
<P>
So far there has been no progress vis a vis the removal of the
coercive atmosphere, he observed.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, he pointed out, there has been the
aggravation of the situation.
</P>
<P>
"India's nuclear doctrine itself is a development serious
enough to make it absolutely unavoidable for us to keep the
question of signing the CTBT open until we can be fully assured
that there is no threat to Pakistan's security and if there is
progress towards the removal of atmosphere of coercion we would
like to honor the commitment we had made."
</P>
<P>
India had also said it would sign the treaty by September, but
it recently made it clear that it would not do so before the
upcoming general election is finished.
</P>
<P>
"So we will have to evaluate the implications of all these
developments before we reach the final decision," Shamshad said.
</P>
</TEXT>
