<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Billions Thought to Be Laundered Through Bank of New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 19 (Xinhua) -- As much as 10 billion U.S.
dollars have been laundered through the Bank of New York in what
is believed to be a major money laundering operation by Russian
organized crime, The New York Times said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said in a report that from last October through March
this year, some 4.2 billion dollars, in more than 10,000
transactions, passed through one account, and investigators
estimate that as much as 10 billion dollars may have flowed
through the bank in that account and related ones since early last
year.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of New York has suspended two employees whose names
had surfaced in the investigation. The two suspects, Natasha
Gurfinkel Kagalovsky and Lucy Edwards, are senior officers in the
Bank's Eastern European division and are married to Russian
businessmen, one of whom is believed by investigators to have
controlled one of the accounts.
</P>
<P>
The report said the accounts under scrutiny at the Bank of New
York have been linked by investigators to a man who is a major
figure in Russian organized crime, Semyon Yukovich Mogilevich. The
suspect is involved in a wide range of activities from arms
trafficking and extortion to prostitution, the report quoted
American and European law enforcement and intelligence agencies as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
