<HEADLINE> Following are the highlights of the diplomatic news released by Xinhua today: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China urges the United States to take more concrete actions to
improve bilateral relations and pave the way for a resumption of
negotiations in China's entry into the World Trade Organization (
WTO), a spokesman said here Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Hu Chusheng, spokesman for the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), said at a press conference that the
current standstill in WTO talks is "totally because of reasons of
the U.S. side."
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the U.S. side would take more concrete actions to
improve Sino-US relations, so that conditions would be created for
a resumption of the talks in China's entry into the WTO."
</P>
<P>
He said that important progress was scored during the latest
round of bilateral talks with a dozen countries in Geneva not long
ago. He described the talks as "constructive."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that China has never changed its
attitude and stance in its bid to enter the multilateral trade
body, and the negotiation process has never been suspended.
</P>
<P>
 Chinese Red Cross Providing Aid For
</P>
<P>
 Turkish Earthquake Victims
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross Society of China today announced that it will
donate 500,000 yuan (about 60,000 U.S.dollars) worth of relief
materials for earthquake-stricken parts of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The materials, mainly tents, food, and medicines, will be
delivered to the affected areas as soon as possible, a Red Cross
official said.
</P>
<P>
China's Foreign Minister Speaks About
</P>
<P>
International Situation
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan, in a report on the international
situation and China's diplomatic work to senior Party and
government officials and military officers here today, said that
the trend toward relaxation in international affairs has not
changed and that peace and development are the two main topics now.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting organized by the Publicity Department of the
Chinese Communist Party Central Committee and other departments,
Tang said that there have been important changes in the
international situation and international relations this year and
today's world is still not peaceful and tranquil and that factors
of instability, uncertainty, and unrest in politics and the
economy and the number of regional ethnic and religious conflicts
and territorial disputes have been increasing. Hegemonism and
power politics are having new development and the issue of
military security is still conspicuous.
</P>
</TEXT>
