<HEADLINE> Today's Diplomatic News Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin, in a meeting with Malaysian Prime
Minister Datuk Seri Mahathir bin Mohamad this morning in the
coastal city of Dalian, praised the visit, which comes in the 25th
anniversary of Sino-Malaysian diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
In the past two and half decades, Jiang said, bilateral
cooperation has had smooth growth in all areas and China is
satisfied with the development.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that Malaysia recognizes only one China and has
adhered to a "one China" policy and that the "two states" remark
of Lee Teng-hui is not accepted by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Jiang stated China's stance on the Taiwan issue and said that
reunification is the will of the Chinese people and is in line
with historic trends and any move that goes against it is doomed
to failure.
</P>
<P>
China and Malaysia have similar views on international issues,
Jiang said, and both sides have enjoyed mutual understanding and
support. China cherishes this cooperation, he said, adding he
hopes that both countries can make an effort to bring a deeper,
broader and better Sino-Malaysian relationship into the new
century.
</P>
<P>
 Outstanding Foreign Affairs Workers Commended
</P>
<P>
Ten young Chinese working in foreign affairs were commended
here today for helping to create a healthy international
environment for Chinese development.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Tong, a 31-year-old interpreter at the Ministry of Foreign
Affairs, was one of those recognized. She has done an excellent
job in interpreting for some top Chinese leaders, including
President Jiang Zemin and Premier Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
Other people included a Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation official who took part in talks on China's accession
to the World Trade Organization and a People's Daily reporter who
risked his life on the battlefield in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, the chairman of China's National People's Congress
Standing Committee, said that the choosing of outstanding foreign
affairs workers through public appraisal was a good way to help
encourage qualified foreign affairs officials, adding he hopes
that the young people will continue to make a contribution to
China's foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
