<HEADLINE> Today's Diplomatic News Highlights (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China increased inspections of imported French wine out of a
need to protect Chinese consumers, a spokesman of the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) said here today.
</P>
<P>
Hu Chusheng, the spokesman, told a press conference organized
by the Information Office of the State Council that The State
Administration for Entry-Exit Inspection and Quarantine issued a
circular recently to all local Chinese customs offices, telling
them to check on wine imported from four specified provinces of
France and to see whether it had an inspection certificate of
French quarantine authorities and whether the wine needed to be re-
examined by the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
 HK Chief Executive to Attend APEC Meeting
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) Tung Chee Hwa will attend the informal leadership
conference of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum
to be held on September 12 and 13 in Auckland, New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The leaders will review progress of APEC's work over the past
10 years, including various initiatives in promoting trade and
investment liberalization and facilitation, and will also review
developments in strengthening the global financial system.
</P>
<P>
They will also discuss other key global challenges, including
APEC's support for the launching of a new round of broad-based
multilateral trade negotiations in the World Trade Organization,
and on Y2K contingency planning.
</P>
