<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Zone Annual Inflation Slightly Up In July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The annual inflation rate in
the 11-member euro zone rose from 0.9 percent to 1.1 percent
between June and July, the European Union (EU) statistics office,
Eurostat, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The rate was 1.3 percent in July 1998, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The annual inflation in the whole of the 15-country EU was up
from 1.0 percent in June to 1.1 percent in July while the rate in
July last year was 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Spain registered the highest rate of 2.1 percent, followed by
Denmark with 2.0 percent, and Ireland and Portugal, both with 1.9
percent, Eurostat reported referring to all 15 EU member states.
</P>
<P>
The lowest rate was in Luxembourg, with -0.3 percent, followed
by Sweden with 0.2 percent, and Austria, with 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Compared with June, annual inflation fell in six EU member
states, rose in five and remained unchanged in four, the report
indicated.
</P>
<P>
Compared to the same period last year, Denmark saw the biggest
relative rise, from 1.4 percent to 2.0 percent, followed by
Finland from 1.1 percent to 1.4 percent while Luxembourg
registered the biggest relative fall from 1.2 percent to -0.3
percent, followed by Sweden from 1.3 percent to 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The lowest 12-month averages up to July were in Sweden, with 0.
2 percent, and Germany, France and Austria, all 0.4 percent while
the highest in Greece, 3.3 percent, Portugal, 2.4 percent, and
Ireland, 2.3 percent, the Eurostat said.
</P>
<P>
Economists in Europe hold that current level of inflation is
not a problem for overall economic picture this year since most of
the economies are showing recovery from relative recession in the
EU region.
</P>
<P>
The euro zone is composed of all EU countries but Britain,
Denmark, Greece, and Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
