<HEADLINE> India Rejects U.S. Concerns of Indo-Pak Nuke Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 19, (Xinhua) -- Indian Foreign Affairs
Minister Jaswant Singh Thursday rejected U.S. concerns of a
possible Indo-Pak nuclear conflict.
</P>
<P>
Singh, who will lead the Indian delegation at the United
Nations General Assembly session in New York next month, said he
is willing to discuss the draft nuclear doctrine with Washington.
</P>
<P>
The draft nuclear doctrine, prepared by the National Security
Advisory Board of India, was released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Asked about Washington's comment that a nuclear conflict was
possible if tensions continued between India and Pakistan, he
said, "I refute suggestions of that possibility."
</P>
<P>
"As far as restraint is concerned, India has been consistently
observing restraint," he said, adding " It is the hall mark of our
international conduct."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the draft nuclear doctrine, he said it was not a
National Security Council doctrine but a document of National
Security Advisory Board. In this document nothing has been said
has not been said earlier.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the prospects of resumption of the stalled
bilateral dialogue with Pakistan, he said that Islamabad's
continued assistance and abatement to cross-border terrorism were
not the "best encouragement" for talks.
</P>
<P>
He also made it clear that there was no place for third party
mediation on Indo-Pak issues as mediators on any sensitive issue
would come forward with their own agenda.
</P>
<P>
"We both do speak the same language and we do not need
interpreters," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
