<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Bars Coup Makers From Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Any country where political power
is usurped through a coup will henceforth earn instant suspension
from the Commonwealth of Nations, Emeka Anyaoku,
secretary-general of the organization, said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper Thursday quoted the
Nigeria- born secretary-general as saying that the 53-nation
organization would offer necessary support to any country willing
to repatriate public funds looted by corrupt officials.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku, who is expected to return to London Thursday after a
three-day visit to Nigeria, said the multinational body fully
backed a recent decision by the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) that coup makers would no longer be welcome in its fold.
</P>
<P>
In a draft resolution at the end of the 35th summit of the OAU
in Algiers on July 14, more than 50 African leaders resolved to
banish coup makers from their midst and outlaw military rule
anywhere on the continent.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku noted that no member-nation of the Commonwealth
currently has a military leader. He stressed that military rule
is "unacceptable" to the organization, which he described as a
custodian of democracy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
