<HEADLINE>   Philippine Fans Raring to Watch Volleyball GP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine fans are very glad
that they get the rare chance to see the world best women
volleyballers in the flesh this time when the World Grand Prix
Women's Volleyball Championship kicks off Friday in Manila.
</P>
<P>
Defending champions Brazil and three other elite teams, Cuba,
Italy and South Korea will test each other's wits in the event's
Manila leg over the coming weekend.
</P>
<P>
South Korea will be first on line for the Cubans with the two
teams clashing in the curtain-raiser at 5:30 p.m. at the
PhilSports Area after the brief ceremonials.
</P>
<P>
The Italians play the Brazilians at 7:30 p.m. in the other game
of the exciting double-header expected to draw a huge crowd.
</P>
<P>
Cuba is expected to redeem itself from its lackluster showing
in the first leg of the 1-million-U.S.-dollar series in Macao
where it lost all of its three games in Macao.
</P>
<P>
"We expect to come out of this leg on top," Cuba's coach
Antonio Perdomo said earlier in a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Bernardo Rocha de Resende, the coach of Brazil which had just
topped the Pan-American Games and won the Macao stop via a sweep,
is not just about to count the Cubans out.
</P>
<P>
"Cuban has been the best in the world for a long time," Resende
said, "Besides, we also lost our first three matches last year. We
won two tournaments and we are champions."
</P>
<P>
The Italians are expected to ride on the tremendous gains they
made in Macao where they won two games while South Korea goes into
the Manila meet with its confidence boosted no end by a big
victory over Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The four teams are actually going for crucial points that will
get them entry into the crossover semifinals where a 370,000-
dollar pot topped by a 200,000-dollar champion's prize is on offer.
</P>
<P>
Competing in the other group in Chinese Taipei are Russia,
Japan, China and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The GP finals will be staged in Yunnan province, China on
August 28-29. 
</P>
