<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Experts Discover Antitumor Effect of Mushrooms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese medical experts have
discovered that medical mushrooms such as Ganoderma (Ling Zhi) and
Coriolus (Yun Zhi) contain important components of increasing the
activity of the immune systems and stimulating the antitumor
effect of the body.
</P>
<P>
Clinical study in 485 cancer patients in Shanghai hospitals
shows that PSP, a derivative of Ganoderma, obviously improved
their symptoms such as poor appetite, tiredness and pain.
</P>
<P>
It also diminished the side effects of radiotherapy and
chemotherapy, according to the 8th International Symposium of
Society of Chinese Bioscientists in America (SCBA) that closed
Thursday in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Medical experts attending the SCBA elaborated on their clinical
trials of derivatives of medical mushrooms in animals and cancer
patients, and said all the results are encouraging.
</P>
<P>
As adjuvant treatment, administration of PSK, a derivative of
Coriolus, increased the survival rate of some 185 lung cancer
patients who underwent radiotherapy.
</P>
<P>
It also improved the 5-year disease-free rate and survival rate
in 262 gastric cancer patients with gastrectomy.
</P>
<P>
Ganoderma and Coriolus have been known for thousands of years
as medical mushrooms used to treat diseases, retard aging and to
prolong life for thousands of years in China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
During the last decade the medical effects of their main
components and their mechanism have been widely studied with
modern scientific methods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
