<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book On Xinhua Journalists Killed in Past 68 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- More than 150 journalists from
the Xinhua News Agency have lost their lives in the line of duty
since Xinhua was founded in 1931, a recently published book
reveals.
</P>
<P>
Shao Yunhuan, a female reporter who was killed during the U.S.-
led NATO attack on the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade on May 8 was
the latest to lose her life.
</P>
<P>
About 70 percent of the journalists were killed during the War
of Resistance Against Japan (1937-1945), but 17 lost their lives
after New China was founded in 1949.
</P>
<P>
The book is entitled "A Record of Deeds of Xinhua Martyrs". It
was compiled by Xinhua's Journalism Research Institute and
published by the Xinhua Publishing House and provides the first
look at many of the journalists' lives.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua was formerly known as the Red China News Agency. It was
founded in Ruijin County of Jiangxi Province in 1931. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earthquake Death Toll Rises to 5,000 in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in Tuesday's
strong earthquake in Turkey has exceeded 5,000, a Turkish source,
who asked no to be named, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The figure was later confirmed by Turkish television reports
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Around 20,000 people were reported to have been injured in the
quake, which struck northwestern Turkey early Tuesday morning, the
source said, adding that another 10,000 people were still missing.
</P>
<P>
As rescue teams reach villages and towns which were initially
cut off from communications with outside, the number of casualties
and injuries may jump dramatically in the coming days, government
officials said.
</P>
<P>
A powerful earthquake struck northwestern Turkish provinces of
Sakarya, Izmit, Istanbul, Yalova, Bolu, Bursa, Zoguldak, Tekirdag
and Eskisehir at 3:02 a.m. (0002 GMT) Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The magnitude of the quake was 7.4 degrees on the Richter
scale, said Ahmed Mete Isikara, the head of Istanbul's Kandilli
Observatory, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports had put the magnitude at 6.7 to 7.8 degrees,
depending on where the measurements were taken.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake was beneath Adapazari province,
formerly a region of Izmit province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
