<HEADLINE> Chinese Bioscientists Find New Ways of Quick Diagnosis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A number of Chinese
bioscientists have presented their recent studies on new disease
diagnostic technology at an international symposium held here.
</P>
<P>
Some 800 Chinese bioscientists from all over the world attended
the Eighth International Symposium of Society of Chinese
Bioscientists in America, which was held from August 14 to 19.
</P>
<P>
Among these new diagnostic approaches was the gene-chip
technology recently developed by Jing-Shan Hu and his colleagues
from Affymetrix Pharmaceutical Inc.
</P>
<P>
"It is a revolutionary progress in the development of
diagnostic technology," said Chan King Ming, associate professor
of the Department of Biochemistry of the Chinese University of
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Gene-chip technology is an approach to design, based on DNA
sequence information, and produce miniature gene-chip probe arrays,
using spatially patterned, light-directed combinatorial chemical
synthesis and containing up to hundreds of thousands of different
oligonucleotides at high density.
</P>
<P>
With these arrays and gene expression profiles, doctors can
accurately identify gene expression events in a very short period
of time, according to Chen.
</P>
<P>
David Ho, a Chinese professor, who is also director of the
Aaron Diamond AIDS Research Center in the United States, also
reported his latest research on AIDS therapies.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 Chinese bioscientists from the United States and
Canada displayed their achievements in biotechnology. Nobel
Laureate Stanley B. Prusiner, Donnall Thomas and Paul Berg also
gave lectures at the symposium and shared their life experiences
in science with local students and teachers during the symposium.
</P>
</TEXT>
