<HEADLINE> Nearly Half of Canadian Adults Overweight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Nearly half of Canadian adults
are overweight, with New Brunswickers being the fattest in the
east while British Columbians the skinniest in the west, according
to Statistics Canada Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agency said 34 percent of Canadians are overweight while
another 12 percent considered obese.
</P>
<P>
The finding is based on a national population health survey
conducted between 1996 and 1997 among 50,347 residents aged 20 to
64.
</P>
<P>
Only 48 percent of the population tips the scales at a healthy
weight while two percent are considered underweight, the agency
indicated.
</P>
<P>
New Brunswickers ranked at the top of the fat list, where 20
percent of the surveyed population were judged obese and another
40 percent overweight. British Columbians are the most slender,
with 12 percent and 10 percent respectively, the agency added.
</P>
<P>
Being heavy could be "a ticking time bomb" triggering off a
series of illness including asthma, arthritis, back problems, high
blood pressure, diabetes and thyroid disorders, a Statistics
Canada source said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
