<HEADLINE> Israel Opens Main Hebron Road to Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Israel Thursday opened a
major thoroughfare in the West Bank city of Hebron to Palestinian
traffic.
</P>
<P>
The thoroughfare was closed more than five years ago after the
massacre of 29 Arabs by a Jewish settler.
</P>
<P>
Peter Lerner, spokesman for Israel's civil administration, said
the majority of Shuhada Street, or Martyrs Street, was opened to
all Palestinian vehicles, except trucks, in both directions.
</P>
<P>
In response, Jewish settlers living in the city said that the
road's opening endangered them and they planned to march to
protest the move.
</P>
<P>
Shuhada Street runs through downtown Hebron, which is still
under Israeli occupation. It links two Jewish enclaves in the
city, where some 450 Jewish settlers live or study.
</P>
<P>
In February 1994, Jewish settler Baruch Goldstein gunned down
29 Muslim worshippers in a Hebron mosque. Since then, Shuhada
Street had been closed by Israel to Palestinian traffic to
prevent friction with settlers.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians have been demanding that the road be opened in
accordance with the signed peace deals with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
