<HEADLINE> Any U.S. Attack on Afghanistan Is a Big Mistake: Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia has
said that it will be a big mistake for the United States if it
launches any attack on Afghanistan under the excuse of Osama
issue.
</P>
<P>
"The last year cruise missile attack on Afghanistan was an
unjustified action. It was an aggression against Afghanistan. I do
not think that the U.S. government would again take such unwise
action," the Islamabad-based News Network International (NNI)
quoted Taliban spokesman Amir Khan Mutaqqi as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mutaqqi stressed in Kabul during an interview with NNI that
differences between the Taliban and the United States should be
resolved through talks.
</P>
<P>
Problems could not be solved through force, Mutaqqi said,
adding that the Taliban are ready to settle issues with Washington
through talks.
</P>
<P>
The United States launched Tomahawk missile attack on the
southern Afghan province of Khost last August in a bid to
eliminate the alleged terrorist bases run by Saudi dissident Osama
bin Laden. However, Osama remained unhurt.
</P>
<P>
Washington accuses Osama of masterminding the bombing of the
American embassies in Tanzania and Kenya on August 7 last year,
which killed more than 220 people including 12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban supreme leader, Mulla Mohammad Omar, has asked the
world community to provide evidence against Osama for his
involvement in the alleged terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
However, no country, including the United States, has so far
provided any proof.
</P>
<P>
"We are very surprised that why the United States is so worried
about Osama, who is unable to operate against any country from
Afghan soil," Mutaqqi said.
</P>
<P>
"Exploitation of the Osama issue is not in the interests of
both Afghanistan and the United States," said Mutaqqi.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Taliban have not invited Osama to Afghanistan
and he has been living in the country before the Taliban captured
Jalalabad and Kabul.
</P>
<P>
"It is Afghanistan's tradition that we protect the person who
takes shelter," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Osama is guest and we will never allow Osama to use Afghan
soil against anybody. When Osama can not operate from Afghanistan
so the United States should not spoil relations with the Taliban
because of Osama," the Taliban spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Restrictions have been imposed on Osama and he can not operate
against anyone from Afghan soil, the Taliban official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
