<HEADLINE> Hazardous Waste Classifications Need to Be Harmonized, EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) said on
Thursday that many of the current international and national
classifications over hazardous waste are not harmonized and it is
complicating data situation in the 15-country EU.
</P>
<P>
"To support politicians in their decisions, there is a clear
need for more precise and reliable statistics based on harmonized
definitions," the EU statistical office, Eurostat, said in a
report.
</P>
<P>
The EU region generated about 27 million tons of hazardous
waste in the mid-1990s and the amount is increasing, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
"Comparisons between countries can only be indicative due to
different classifications and definitions used by each country,"
it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The report said that hazardous waste is a very sensitive topic
for different sectors in European society.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, politicians and the public have become aware
of the dangers of hazardous waste to the environment and to the
population, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Eurostat, which analyzes the situation on hazardous waste
every two years, said last two years saw falls of hazardous waste
in Germany, the Netherlands and Britain, but increasing tendencies
in Belgium, Denmark, Spain, Austria and Norway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
