<HEADLINE> Visit by Americans to Chinese End-Users Resumed: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Visits by Americans to end-users
of U.S. technical exports to China that were suspended after May
have been resumed, a spokesman of the Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) said here today.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC spokesman Hu Chusheng told reporters at a press
conference organized by the Information Office of the State
Council that MOFTEC has arranged visits by the U.S. side to some
end-users in Beijing this month.
</P>
<P>
Under the MOFTEC arrangement, the U.S. side has visited end-
users at the China Meteorological Administration and with the
Beijing Municipal Traffic Control Administration, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since China and the United States reached an understanding on
visits to end-users in June last year, China arranged six such
visits in 1998, rather than "one visit" as claimed by the Cox
report, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
This year, the U.S. side has so far put forward more than 40
requests to visit Chinese end-users, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S.-led NATO missile attack against the Chinese embassy
in Belgrade last May severely hurt the feelings of the Chinese
people, and therefore the arrangements of such visits were
suspended thereafter," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hu said China resumed the arrangement of visits in August to
show its "sincerity in cooperation." He said the U.S. side voiced
no objection to those arrangements.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that visits to end-users can effectively loosen the
restriction the U.S. side has imposed on export of hi-tech
products to China, thus helping the smooth growth of hi-tech trade
between the two countries," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
