<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Risk Investment Needed to Promote Industrialization of High-Tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The development of risk
investment in China can help promote the industrialization of high
technology, said Cheng Siwei, vice-chairman of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress, today.
</P>
<P>
We are hopeful that China can build up an improved risk
investment system within five to ten years by establishing
consultative and management companies and setting up funds for
risk investment, Cheng told the ongoing symposium "Invigorating
China Through Science and Education" in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Since risk investment goes mainly into the development of new
technology and products, it involves fairly large risks, Cheng
said, and the successful rate for such investment is only about 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
To disperse risks, this investment usually goes to a group of
more than ten projects so that money earned from the successful
projects can be used to make up for the losses of the unsuccessful
ones, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Cheng pointed out that to promote the development of risk
investment in China, problems such as the selection of promising
projects and the accumulation of necessary funds must be solved.
</P>
<P>
China must establish risk investment consulting and management
companies to assess and recommend risk investment projects to
domestic and overseas investors and manage these projects as
mandated by the investors, he said.
</P>
<P>
Also, risk investment funds should be set up and corresponding
laws, regulations, and management rules formulated to absorb funds
from both home and broad.
</P>
<P>
The practice of risk investment began in China in 1985 with the
establishment of the China New Technology Development and
Investment Corporation. Scientific and technological development
and investment companies and relevant funds were set up in some
areas later on, and risk investment funds based on overseas
capital began to enter China in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
These companies and funds have made a variety of contributions
to the development of high technology in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Suggests Increased Fund for Basic Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- China should increase spending
on basic research projects, especially those which are related to
national scientific and technological development goals, a Chinese
scientist suggested here today.
</P>
<P>
The fund for research and development (R&AMP;D) should be raised
from the current 0.5 percent of the gross domestic product to 1.5
percent, said Zhang Cunhao, president of the National Natural
Science Foundation of China.
</P>
<P>
As a major source of innovation, basic research is, directly or
indirectly, giving impetus to economic growth and social progress,
Zhang told the ongoing symposium "Invigorating China Through
Science and Education" in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
He said that basic research is providing an important basis for
reforming and upgrading traditional industries in China, and noted
that a portion of basic research should be geared to new and high
technology.
</P>
<P>
He said that the National Natural Science Foundation of China
has decided to raise the percentage for pure research to 42.5
percent of the total investment in both pure and applied research,
compared with only 30 percent last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
