<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APT, LORAL Sign Long-term Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 19 (Xinhua) -- APT Satellite Holdings Limited,
a Hong Kong-based satellite service provider, and Loral Space and
Communications Limited have agreed to lease substantially all of
APT's APSTAR-IIR transponders for the remaining life of the
satellite.
</P>
<P>
This will bring the total utilization of the satellite close to
its full capacity.
</P>
<P>
With this contract, APT will receive a satisfactory and stable
revenue of 304 million U.S. dollars over the coming years. And
LORAL, in turn, will significantly increase its transponder
capacity in the Asia Pacific region, establishing a solid foothold
in the broadcasting and telecommunications business in the region
and further enhancing its global satellite network.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the lease rental will be settled over 18
installments within a period of four years. With this substantial
income, APT will further strengthen its financial position and
will be able to re-allocate its efforts and capital resources in
developing, as planned, additional high-power satellites, such as
APSTAR-III and APSTAR-IV as well as APSTAR-V (a replacement
satellite for APSTAR-I).
</P>
<P>
The lease income will also help finance APT's expansion into
satellite-related businesses, such as VSAT services in China,
Internet service network as well as satellite television uplink
and downlink services licensed by the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) government in July 1999.
</P>
<P>
"We are all very encouraged and excited about this cooperation
between APT and LORAL which will bring forth mutual benefits and
long-term business opportunities in the region," APT vice-chairman
and president He Ke-rang said.
</P>
<P>
Nicholas Moren, senior vice president and treasurer of LORAL,
said that the contract demonstrates LORAL'S growing commitment for
the region.
</P>
<P>
"The APSTAR-IIR offers our customers powerful footprints and
adds significant Asia Pacific capacity to the growing resources of
the LORAL," he said.
</P>
<P>
APSTAR-IIR, a three-axis body-stabilized FS-1300 geostationary
satellite supplied by Space Systems/Loral Inc., is the third in-
orbit satellite of APT which was successfully launched on board a
Long March 3B launch vehicle on October 17, 1997. It has very
broad footprints covering over 100 countries across Asia, Europe
and Africa and Australia, or approximately 75 percent of the world
's population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
