<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian New Government Inherits 2.7 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's new civilian
administration inherited a budget deficit of more than 256
billion naira (about 2.7 billion U.S. dollars) on resumption of
office on May 29, reported a Nigerian newspaper Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Minister of Finance Mallam Ciroma, said in Abuja on
Wednesday that the government had been financing the deficit by
borrowing from the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
Government was compelled to take this precautionary measure to
avoid destabilizing the macro-economic stability of the nation,
though the borrowings from the central bank led to an increase in
inflation rate from eight percent to 12 percent, the Guardian, a
major Nigerian newspaper Thursday quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on factors that necessitated the supplementary
budget, which was recently presented to the National Assembly as
a draft bill, Ciroma further explained that increase in the wages
and salaries of workers showed and the 1999 budget could no
longer finance government's commitment.
</P>
<P>
He added that the advent of a new government and the
establishment of new ministries and parastatals also indicated
that the 1999 budget needed to be revised. 
</P>
