<HEADLINE> Thailand, Myanmar to Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Myanmar are forging
closer ties and strengthening cooperation as the two countries are
planning to sign agreements on cultural exchange and visa
exemption for diplomats and officials, the official Thai News
Agency (TNA) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony will be held in the Rangoon, capital of
Myanmar, at the Fifth Joint Commission meeting between the two
countries to be held from August 23 to 25, TNA said.
</P>
<P>
The agreements followed an accord on cooperation in the
suppression of drug trafficking along the border, which was
reached at a meeting of senior Thai and Myanmar officials held in
Thailand's southern province of Ranong this week.
</P>
<P>
At the Joint Commission meeting, Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan and his Myanmar counterpart Win Maung would further
discuss jointly cracking down on cross-border crimes, including
drug trade, and car smuggling and other issues like illegal
workers and refugees, TNA said.
</P>
<P>
To promote trade and tourism, Thailand would propose that
Rangoon grant visas to Thai tourists traveling through
international channels.
</P>
<P>
Maritime conflicts over controversial waters and measures to
tackle the casino operations at the Golden Triangle area along the
Thai-Myanmar-Lao border will also top the agenda of the Joint
Commission meeting, according to TNA. 
</P>
