<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Chinese Accepting The Idea Of A "Tree Burial" For Their Funeral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- More of the Chinese elderly here
are getting used to the idea of having their ashes buried under a
trees after they die instead of in a graveyard.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Yuhuan, a 78-year-old retired construction worker, is one
advocate of the method and says that it's the best reform since
the 10 million babies born in China every year and the water and
soil erosion, desertification, and construction are causing a
rapid decrease in the amount of land.
</P>
<P>
The tree burial saves land resources and contributes to
afforestation say civil affairs department officials. Most of the
ashes of deceased people are now put in graveyards in Taiyuan, the
capital of Shanxi Province, where there are 7 cemeteries. Yong'an
Yuan (Eternal Peace Garden) is one example. A 1.5-sq.m. plot there
costs as much as 4,200 yuan (about 500 U.S. dollars), and a 2-sq.m.
plot for a couple goes for 6,000 to as much as 50,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Tree burial is comparatively economical and trouble-free. All
that is needed is a hole in the ground where the ashes of the dead
are put and a tree planted. The cost is about 200 to 300 yuan.
</P>
<P>
"I don't believe in rebirth, I just want my burial to be simple
and not too much of a financial burden for my children," says Wang
Xiaoban, a retired worker, who adds that pines are evergreens and
represent eternity, so a tree burial is the best way to keep the
elderly "safe and happy until they return to the earth" and the
need to commemorate the dead.
</P>
<P>
The cities of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai, Guangzhou, and
Shenyang are all pushing tree burials and sea burials. Nanjing,
one of the first to advocate tree burials, recently issued a
notice that the local government will not allow any more land to
be used for graveyards, with the final goal of saving no ashes and
occupying no land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
