<HEADLINE> IMF to Raise Thai Export Forecast to 3.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Supachai, also Commerce Minister, was quoted by Thailand News
Agency as saying that the expected upward revision was based on
three reasons, including a steadily upward trend of Thai exports
over the past four months, stabilization of prices level and
stable exchange rates of Thai currency baht.
</P>
<P>
IMF informed the Thai government that given the positive
factors it would revise growth forecast of Thai Exports this year
from the previous figure of 2 percent to a revised 3.5 percent,
Supachai said.
</P>
<P>
Based on the IMF new projection, the Thai economy could grow by
as much as 3 percent this year, from the government's earlier
forecast of 1 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Supachai also said that he still believed the country's exports
this year could achieve the government's target of 4 percent,
citing that a latest report by the Board of Investment (BOI)
showed that production and export of locally-made products in key
industries under its supervision grew by 8 percent in the first
seven months of this year.
</P>
<P>
BOI oversees 46 percent of the country's overall exports.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister earlier projected that Thai exports
next year could grow by 5 percent as the Thai economy was steadily
recovering from its worst crisis in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry announced earlier this week that overall
Thai exports in the January-July period accounted for 32.21
billion U.S. dollars, an increase of 592 million dollars or 1.9
percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government and the IMF are expected to complete a
quarterly review of the Thai economy this week. They are expected
to give an upbeat assessment of Thailand's recovery prospects in
the report likely to be announced by the government late this
month. 
</P>
