<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Coastal City Continues Opening Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The city of Beihai on the south
China coast in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region used 21.54
million U.S. dollars worth of foreign direct investment in the
first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
This was an increase of 69.34 percent over the same period last
year. Beihai also had increases in foreign trade from January to
June. Mayor Jin Renshou says that the city's efforts to improve
the database and management of projects and to promote investment
in the first half of the year paid off.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors have shown strong interest in the city's
sectors of tourism, technology, marine resources, and agriculture
and 12 overseas-financed projects with 15.63 million U.S. dollars
were approved.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade departments have explored new markets while
solidifying traditional export markets. The city increased exports
of fireworks, farm pesticides, and leather products from January
to June.
</P>
<P>
The city is on a 107-kilometer coastline with a 2,000-year
history of merchant vessels sailing west to the Indian Ocean,
through the Malay Peninsula, and up along Myanmar's coast. With
Southeast Asia just across the bay and Hong Kong and Macao close,
Beihai is a natural exit for parts of China farther inland. Its
geographical position, infrastructure, and improved "software"
environment have made it more appealing to domestic businessmen.
</P>
<P>
