<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Evidence Of Japanese Use Of "Comfort Women" In Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- China's historians have
discovered new evidence in the city of Tianjin on the use of "
comfort women", or women who were forced to provide sexual
services to Japanese troops during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Many original documents have been found, including orders from
the Japanese military and the numbers and names of some of
comfort women.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Hongxiang, a scholar of the anti-Japanese war, says that
these archives are merely the tip of the iceberg. Tianjin was a
military base for the Japanese invaders and a major area for the
forceful recruiting of such women. Zhang estimates that there must
have been more than 1,000 "comfort women" taken in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Several sites used for sexual favors at that time have been
found in the city and historians are asking survivors to reveal
their identities to expose the atrocities of the Japanese invaders.
</P>
<P>
Historians estimate that up to 200,000 women throughout Asia
were forced to supply sexual services to Japanese troops during
the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
