<HEADLINE> APEC Members Won't Accept Two-States Theory: Thai Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Lee Teng-hui's so-called
"two-states theory" will not be accepted by members of the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC), a senior Thai Foreign
Ministry official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Kobsak Chutikul, director of the Thai Foreign Ministry's
Economic Department, made the remark in the ministry when asked
about the upcoming APEC informal leadership conference in New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
APEC members, which abide by the one-China policy, hold that
Taiwan attends the APEC meetings as an economic entity within
China and that the "two-states" theory is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Lee Teng-hui said in early July that Taiwan should handle its
relations with mainland China on a "state-to-state" basis.
</P>
<P>
Several members of the APEC have sent messages to Taiwan,
warning the island that it will not get support if it raises the
"two-states" issue at the APEC informal leadership conference,
scheduled in mid-September, Kobsak said.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand's stance has always been clear that Taiwan is not a
state, not a sovereign state at all," Kobsak said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
