<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals on Rise in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals in the first
six months of this year in Cambodia recorded a 37 percent increase
compared with the same period of last year, according to official
figures published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The number of visitor arrivals in the first half of the year
reached 307,444, with nearly half of them entering Cambodia
through Thailand to visit the historic site in Preah Vihear which
were newly opened to the public.
</P>
<P>
The number of Chinese visitors is also increasing. According to
a report of the Ministry of Tourism, more than 12,000 people from
China (excluding Hong Kong) arrived in Cambodia by air in the
first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia earned 33 million U.S. dollars in tourism in the first
six months of this year while in 1998 the figure was 60 million
U.S. dollars. Each foreign visitor spent 87 U.S. dollars,
excluding the visa fee.
</P>
<P>
The tourism authorities estimated that the tourism revenue this
year will increase sharply. Tourism is one of the most promising
industries of Cambodia which boasts the centuries-old temples,
regarded as among the most magnificent monuments in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
