<HEADLINE> Japanese Women Call For Resumption 0f Dialogue With Pyongyang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A group of Japanese women Thursday
called on the Japanese government to lift sanctions against the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and resume dialogue
with it to normalize diplomatic relations, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The call was contained in a petition submitted to Chief Cabinet
Secretary Hiromu Nonaka by Sumiko Shimizu, a House of Councillors
member from the Social Democratic Party (SDP) and leader of the
Japan Women's Federation of Associations for Solidarity with
Korean Women, and three other members of the group.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese women said the government should resume offering
humanitarian aid to the DPRK and holding dialogue with the country
to respond to a statement released by Pyongyang on August 10.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK statement said, "If Japan opts to open good-neighborly
relations through liquidation of the past, the DPRK will welcome
it with pleasure."
</P>
<P>
The statement also called on Japan to apologize and provide
compensations for "all its past crimes."
</P>
<P>
Japan imposed the sanctions, including freezing food aid and
suspending talks for normalizing diplomatic ties, following DPRK's
launch on August 31 last year of a three-stage rocket, part of
which flew over Japan before splashing into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang said the rocket was for sending a satellite into
orbit, but Japan has maintained it was the test launch of a
ballistic missile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
