<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residence Of Author Of Classical Chinese Novel Discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The residence of Cao Xueqin, who
wrote the classical Chinese novel "Dream of Red Mansions" in the
mid-18th century, was discovered in Beijing recently.
</P>
<P>
The 17-room compound with a courtyard is located on Guangqumen
Street in the southeastern part of Beijing. It had been broken up
for 20-some households.
</P>
<P>
Cao's great grandfather, grandfather, father, and uncle all
held administrative posts in Jiangning Prefecture (present-day
Nanjing and surrounding counties) and his great grandmother helped
nurse Emperor Kangxi.
</P>
<P>
In the fifth year of the Emperor Yongzheng reign (1727), the
Cao family who had been favored by the previous emperor, were
accused of embezzling funds and their estates were confiscated and
they fell into disgrace and moved from Jiangning to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Some scholars and members of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) in Beijing recently met twice at
Cao's former residence and said that the number of rooms and the
layout of the compound tally exactly with the description in a
document from Chinese historical archives.
</P>
<P>
One scholar said that the characters for "dignified and upright
" on screens in the eastern part of the courtyard appeared in "
Dream of Red Mansions".
</P>
<P>
Feng Qiyong, the director of the "Dream of Red Mansions"
Research Institute, asked for the restoration of the compound to
make it a popular site for visitors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
