<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nature Reserve Being Sealed Off For Afforestation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'NING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The government of northwest
China's Qinghai Province has decided to close the Hol Xil Nature
Reserve to livestock grazing and wild animal hunting by early next
year to help its afforestation drive, a government official
announced here recently.
</P>
<P>
The move is intended to protect the rare wildlife and plants in
the region and to preserve the ecology, according to Lu Wenzheng,
a provincial government official in charge of the program.
</P>
<P>
Hol Xil is the largest wildlife zone in China. It has 250 types
of wild animals and plants including the Tibetan antelope, wild
yak, and snow leopard, living at an average elevation of 5,000
meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
There have been at least 60,000 people in Hol Xil this year
digging up medicinal herbs, prospecting for gold, or hunting rare
animals, Lu said. China has cracked down on poaching Tibetan
antelope and other rare animals there on many occasions. A major
raid earlier this year netted 13 groups of poachers and 388
Tibetan antelope hides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
