<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's First Giant Panda Triplets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A giant panda at the Chengdu
Giant Panda Breeding Research Center in southwest China's Sichuan
Province has given birth to three cubs, the first recorded birth
of giant panda triplets.
</P>
<P>
The center's director, Zhang Hemin, said today that the cubs
weighed around 140 g. each at birth on Wednesday. The mother and
the cubs are in good condition. Two are now with the mother and
the third is being taken care of by staff members.
</P>
<P>
The 15-year-old mother had had six cubs, four of which survived.
She was artificially inseminated last April. China used artificial
insemination to produce the first giant panda cub in 1963. Fewer
than 10 percent of the center's males and 24 percent of its
females are able to mate by themselves.
</P>
<P>
The 30-hectare center, located at the Wolong Nature Reserve in
the northern suburbs of Chengdu, was developed by the Chinese
government and the World Wildlife Fund (WWF) in 1980 and has
successfully bred 24 giant pandas since 1991, of which 15 survived.
</P>
<P>
Giant pandas have one or two cubs each time. A new giant panda
cub was born at the Chongqing Zoo in southwest China's Chongqing
Municipality earlier this month. There are only about 1,000 giant
pandas both in captivity and in the wild across the world, 80
percent of them in Sichuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Risky Investment Being Experimented With in Western China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cheng Siwei, the vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress, proposed that the risky investment
business be developed at a national conference early last year and
a Ministry of Science and Technology official says that the state
will soon have a series of regulations on risky investment to
protect the rights of investment companies.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government set aside 1 billion yuan for a technical
innovation fund for small and medium-sized high-tech enterprises
at the end of June and, by now, a number of overseas investors are
prepared to get involved in China's risky investment development.
In the past one and a half year, 20 overseas companies have come
to Xi'an to study the situation. Hong Kong's Venture Soft Capital
Co. and Vertex Management (II) of Singapore are experimenting with
venture capital in two high-tech enterprises of the zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
