<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Urges Communities to Back Anti-Drug Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
voiced the hope that communities would help anti-drug operatives
to crack down drug traffickers following the launching of
village-based strike operations.
</P>
<P>
The operations, aimed at combatting narcotic abusers and
traffickers, are now being carried out by the Village Anti-Drug
Abuse Councils, Philippine News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Jewel Canso, head of the National Drug Law
Enforcement Prevention Coordinating Center, as saying that
villages nationwide are preparing for the anti-drug operations by
providing his office with a list of suspected drug pushers in the
community.
</P>
<P>
Canso said these watch lists also include known drug users with
connections to drug traffickers operating outside the community as
well.
</P>
<P>
"These will also be the subjects of preventive operations," he
said, adding that coordination will be enhanced between the
village councils and his center.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government is now in the middle stage of a war
against the drug trade, which is deemed as a major threat to the
youth and a major cause of heinous crimes.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada has vowed to impose the
full force of the law against drug traffickers, ruling out
granting pardon to anyone sentenced to death for drug trafficking.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
