<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Trade Unions Federation Elects New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 19 (Xinhua) -- South African Democratic
Teachers' Union leader Willy Madisha was on Thursday elected as
the new president of the Congress of South African Trade Unions
(Cosatu).
</P>
<P>
Cosatu, together with the South African Communist Party, is in
political alliance with the ruling African National Congress
(ANC).
</P>
<P>
Madisha was elected at Cosatu's special congress in Midrand,
north of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Madisha garnered 1,623 of the 2,130 votes cast against the 498
votes for the only other candidate, Vusi Nhlapo, the president of
the National Education, Health and Allied Workers' Union.
</P>
<P>
Cosatu acting president Peter Malepe won the race for the first
vice presidency with 1,177 votes.
</P>
<P>
Acting general secretary Swelinzima Vavi was confirmed as the
union's general secretary, having stood unopposed for the
position. Tony Ehrenreich of the National Union of Metal Workers
of South Africa was elected deputy general secretary.
</P>
<P>
Adina Ransulase of the South African Catering and Commercial
Allied Workers' Union was elected unopposed for the post of
treasurer.
</P>
<P>
Cosatu and the ANC are believed to be in uneasy terms as the
country enters a period of active industrial action.
Telecommunications workers are on strike, disrupting certain
services of the state telephone company, Telkom, and the Post
Office. Wage talks between the government and 12 public sector
unions are still deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
ANC national chairman, Patrick Lekota, who spoke at the Cosatu
congress on behalf of ANC President Thabo Mbeki, Wednesday chided
the trade union federation for publicly criticizing the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
