<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Boom For Southern Chinese Island Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, August 19 (Xinhua)-- China's southernmost island
province, Hainan, had 4.3 million tourists from January to June,
up 6.8 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Some 200,000 were overseas tourists, a 4.6 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Hainan is China's second-largest island after Taiwan. It used
to be under the jurisdiction of Guangdong Province, but, in 1988,
became China's 30th province and the country's largest economic
zone.
</P>
<P>
Hainan Province has 3 cities, 16 counties, and islands and
reefs of the Xisha, Nansha, and Zhongsha islands. Its unique
tropical scenery has been used to make it one of the country's
most popular tourist destinations. In the past two years, it has
tried to standardize tourist services to add appeal.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, it had over 8 million tourists, compared to a total
population of 7.43 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
