<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopians Fight in Kenyan Border Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Fighting has broken out between
Oromo Liberation Front militiamen and Ethiopian troops in Taki and
Githeer areas of Mandera District in Kenya's North Eastern
Province, bordering Ethiopia and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Sounds of heavy artillery and bombardment could be heard from
Takaha Town, 30 kilometers from Taki, where the battle has been
raging since Monday, the Daily Nation newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported last weekend that about 300 rebels from
the Oromo Liberation Front of Ethiopia had been spotted in the
Malaba hills of northern part of North Eastern Province, who were
forced out of their camps in Somalia by the Ethiopian troops.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kenyan security forces are closing in the remote
hills along the Ethiopian border where the armed Ethiopian rebels
are hiding themselves there.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan villagers have moved from Taki and Githeer to Takaba
Town where residents expressed fear that the fighting could
extend to the area as defeated Oromo rebels are said to be
retreating toward the town.
</P>
<P>
Mandera District Commissioner James Seriani said he had
dispatched a contingent of security personnel to the scene for
getting information of the fighting, and the provincial
administration also launched an operation to flush out the rebels
from the hills.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, the Ethiopian government claimed
last Thursday its army had killed more than 700 Oromo Liberation
Front rebels in the east of the country over the past two months
and a half, while the rebel front said last Friday its soldiers
had put 1,500 Ethiopian government forces out of action during
the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
