<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Talks with the Palestinian National Authority broke down
Wednesday night over the issue of prisoner release. The meeting
was broke up after the government's negotiator, Gilad Sher, told
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat that the security cabinet
decided not to change criteria for releasing prisoners set by the
previous government, and would therefore only be letting out a
limited number of political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Osama El Baz, one of President Hosni Mubarak's most senior
advisors, earlier this week demanded that Israel agree to nuclear
disarmament under the supervision of the International Atomic
Energy Agency. He called for the entire region to become a
nuclear-free zone within five to seven years. He said if Israel
did not agree to dismantle its nuclear program, the Arabs would
feel threatened, and would develop non-conventional weapons
systems of their own, based on chemical and biological
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- In a conciliatory gesture to PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat,
the government Wednesday released one long-term prisoner Khalil
Arai, a Gaza native and a member of the Fatah movement. He was
sentenced to life imprisonment in 1974 for the murder of an
Israeli police officer.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Ahronot:
</P>
<P>
-- An Israeli military rescue team set out Wednesday night
from Istanbul to try to rescue at lease 14 Israelis believed to
have been trapped in rubble in the Turkish resort of Chiben Shik,
the army spokesman said. Another six Israelis are reported
missing. The Israel Police representative in Istanbul told the
Israeli news agency Itim that three Israeli families had turned
to the Israeli consulate for help after their relatives in the
resort could not be located. 
</P>
</TEXT>
