<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Steps Up Assistance to Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Australia has stepped up its
development activities in Nepal, The Kathmandu Post reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Australian aid is currently supporting over thirty Australian
Community Assistance Schemes (ACAS) and Direct Aid Program (DAP)
projects in Nepal with special focus on child labor, health,
governance, education and assistance to vulnerable groups.
</P>
<P>
The ACAS projects enable funding of small but effective aid
activities in Nepal, and under the DAP scheme, development
cooperation support is extended.
</P>
<P>
Projects for the construction of school premises, and the
promotion of mushroom production technology have also been
implemented by Australia's aid.
</P>
<P>
A grant of 786,320 Australia dollars (491,000 U.S. dollars) and
43,000 Australia dollars (27,000 U.S. dollars) was allocated under
ACAS and DAP projects during the 1998/99 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Nepal heavily depends on foreign aid, its net outstanding debt
standing at 2.49 billion U.S. dollars by April 1998. Its major
donors are America, Western Europe, the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
