<HEADLINE> Israel to Sell Missiles to South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Rafael, the armaments
development Authority of Israel, has signed a huge contract with
the South Korea to sell its advanced missiles.
</P>
<P>
The contract, which was also approved by Lockheed Martin
Company of the United States, is worth 100 million U.S. dollars,
local daily Haaretz reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the contract, Rafael will supply air-to-ground
Popeye missiles to the South Korean Air Force.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Department of Defense has approved the deal, meaning
that it can be carried out immediately.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel has also received a request from the Greek
air force to purchase the missile, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The request is currently being examined to see if it could
adversely affect Israel's security or diplomatic interests.
</P>
<P>
The Popeye missile was developed by Rafael and is manufactured
by the Pegasus Corporation, which is jointly owned by Rafael and
Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
The missile is considered one of the most reliable and
technologically advanced of its kind, and has already been
supplied to several air forces, including those of the United
States, Israel and Australia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish air force has already placed an order which is
currently in the pipeline. Total sales of the missile have
reached approximately 600 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
