<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High-Tech Advancing Guangdong Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 19 (Xinhua) --High-tech has been playing a
bigger role in promoting industrial development of south China's
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the province accomplished 137.9 billion
yuan in industrial added value in the first seven months of the
year, up 13.26 percent over the same period last year. And the
production-to-marketing ratio edged up 0.13 percentage points to
hit 96.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Provincial officials say that the wider use of high-tech is a
major factor sustaining the industrial surge.
</P>
<P>
High-tech industrial enterprises in Guangdong now manufacture
more than 2,700 varieties of commodities. From January to July,
five high-tech enterprises in the cities of Shenzhen and Dongguan
chalked up 13.9 billion yuan in output value, contributing 2.99
percentage points to the province's industrial growth.
</P>
<P>
The Shenzhen Science and Technology Industrial Development Park,
jointly established by the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) and
the Shenzhen Municipal Government in 1985, is now home to 80
businesses, including 12 high-tech enterprises set up by CAS
institutes and ventures financed by multinationals like IBM and
Philips.
</P>
<P>
The park has averaged annual growth of 80 percent or 3.6
billion yuan in industrial output value since 1993. Businesses in
the park generated a combined output value of 19.3 billion yuan in
1998, including 17 billion yuan from high-tech firms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
