<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rallies to Be Staged Against Charter Change in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Tens of thousands of people from
different sectors in the Philippines are expected to join a
protest rally set for Friday to force the government to drop its
Charter change agenda.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said the number of the people to attend the
August 20 rally led by former president Crazon Aquino and Manila
Archbishop Jaime Sin will range from 10,000 to half a million.
</P>
<P>
The protest-rally reports came amid the government's proposal
to revise some provisions of the 1987 Philippine Constitution.
</P>
<P>
The Charter revision or amendment is said to involve political
changes as well as economic reform, both of which seem to be
intolerable moves to the demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
Other reports said groups opposing the charter changes have
planned simultaneous protest rallies in at least nine major cities
all over the country on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nine nongovernmental groups are also reportedly joining hands
to lend support to the Friday rally in Makati, Manila.
</P>
<P>
Threats from the New People's Army to bomb the rally and
assassinate rally organizers, Aquino and Cardinal Sin, have
prompted police and military officials to put their troops on
alert around Manila.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government is giving heads of schools and
private offices directions to suspend classes and work in Manila
on Friday in anticipation of the mass rallies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
