<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Booming Development Zone In Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Chongqing Economic and
Technological Development Zone in southwest China reported rapid
development in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The zone's gross domestic product increased a year-on-year 41.
23 percent and its industrial added value surged 47.8 percent
during the period. Financial revenue and trade volume of the
development zone soared 51.5 percent and 37.2 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Since its founding in 1990, the zone, which was approved as a
state-level one in 1993, has invested a total of 900 million yuan
to build infrastructure facilities and develop 32,000 sq. km. of
land.
</P>
<P>
Between 1993 and 1998, the zone's gross domestic product
totaled 6.22 billion yuan and its industrial added value stood at
13.5 billion yuan, registering an annual increase of 25.8 percent
and 49.3 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment in the zone has reached 1.13 billion U.S.
dollars, with investors coming from 23 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, the zone had 1,200 registered enterprises,
including more than 250 overseas-funded ones. The number of
overseas-financed enterprises involving an investment of over 10
million U.S. dollars each reached 21.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications, food processing, automobile, pharmaceutical
and bioengineering are the four pillar industries of the
development zone which aims to achieve 10 billion yuan in gross
domestic product by 2010.
</P>
<P>
At that time, both the zone's actual use of foreign capital and
its foreign trade volume will reach one billion dollars. Its
industrial added value will be 30 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
