<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Recovery Benefits HK Electronics Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The gradual revival of
electronics production in Southeast Asian economies in recent
months should bode well for Hong Kong's electronics industry,
according to a report just published by the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council (TDC).
</P>
<P>
The report said that as Singapore and Taiwan's electronics
exports have started to pick up, demand for Hong Kong's parts and
components will increase.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's exports of parts and components to Singapore were
up seven percent in 1998 to 2,061 million U.S. dollars compared
with 1997. The exports grew by a further two percent in the first
quarter of 1999. Though total exports of electronics products to
China's Taiwan remain uninspiring in the first quarter, the report
expects orders from the island's electronics industry to pick up.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Hong Kong and the two economies have
different product mixes, with only very few items overlapping. The
differences in product assortment and industry nature have
resulted in limited competition.
</P>
<P>
The picture is quite contrary to an earlier perception that
Hong Kong would be threatened by price competition of electronics
products from Singapore and Taiwan due to currency depreciation in
the two economies.
</P>
<P>
The two economies are indeed niche markets for local
electronics exporters, says the report, adding that both of them
have a strong base of manufacturing, creating demand for certain
electronics parts and components for their export production.
</P>
<P>
Singapore needs to source a wide range of parts and components,
particularly the low-to-medium-range items from Hong Kong for
manufacturing finished and semi-finished electronic devices.
</P>
<P>
Also, Singapore has to import a wide range of consumer
electronics due to a narrow scope of its finished goods for local
consumption, thus creating a niche for Hong Kong exporters.
</P>
<P>
To tap the Singapore market, the report suggests that local
exporters of simple consumer electronics consider direct sales to
respective manufacturers and larger retailers in Singapore, saying
that these items have standard specifications, and less reliance
on technical support and after-sales service.
</P>
<P>
For the sales of electronics products to China's Taiwan, the
report says that a marketing network is required as Taiwan is much
larger than Singapore. Selling to trading companies, which can
usually promote sales on their own account in most parts of the
island, is one of the viable options for Hong Kong exporters.
</P>
<P>
In addition to market analysis, entry strategies, distribution
channels and latest development of the industry in Singapore and
Taiwan, the report also provides useful information on the
Singapore Science Park, Taiwan's Hsinchu Science-based Industrial
Park, trade events and exhibitions, contacts of government
departments, agencies and business associations of the two places
for handy reference.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Singapore and Taiwan were respectively the fourth and
sixth largest markets of Hong Kong for electronics products. The
two economies together absorb around 10 percent of Hong Kong's
total electronics exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
