<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient City in East China Becomes Industrial Powerhouse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A high and new-tech zone is
making the ancient Chinese city of Suzhou, eastern Jiangsu
Province, an industrial powerhouse. Today, Suzhou New District (
SND), seven years in existence, contributes more than half of the
city's total industrial output value and exports.
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months of this year, SND exported 690
million U.S. dollars worth of goods and produced an industrial
output value of 13.34 billion yuan (1.6 billion U.S. dollars), up
42 percent and 66.4 percent respectively from the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
SND, located on the western outskirts of Suzhou, covers 52 sq.
km. It was established in 1992 to attract high-tech investment
from both foreign and Chinese businesses. its location at the
center of the southern jiangsu industrial belt with Shanghai a
mere 80 km to the east and its superior transport conditions give
it all the attractiveness it is expected to have.
</P>
<P>
A rapid development of high-tech industries has contributed to
SND's impressive performance. The number of high-tech enterprises
in the district recognized as such by the state has increased to
107. A growing number of them are beginning to enjoy the benefit
of economies of scale. Annually, for example, the district
produces 50 million computer mice, 14 million liquid crystal
display boards, six million color monitors, 400,000 scanners and
two million computer motherboards. Close to 30 enterprises in the
district export more than 10 million U.S. dollars each annually.
</P>
<P>
So far, total investment in the district has exceeded four
billion U.S. dollars, with most of it going into Chinese-foreign
joint ventures. Of more than 340 such firms and over 2,000
domestic operations in the district, 70 percent have been put into
production. The annual output value of 34 of them has exceeded 100
million yuan each.
</P>
<P>
Good economic performance has benefited both Chinese and
foreign partners. Suzhou Philips Consumer Electronics Co., a joint
venture between Suzhou's phoenix TV Factory and Philips of the
Netherlands, became profitable two years after it went into
operation. In 1998, its profit exceeded 170 million yuan. Suzhou
No. 3 Optical Instrument Factory has established in the district
four joint ventures with Japanese and Hong Kong businesses. Its
assets have since increased by close to 30 times.
</P>
<P>
"Given the development momentum, Suzhou New District's economic
growth for the whole of this year is expected to exceed 40 percent,
" said Zhou Yi, an official of the district's Information Office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Couple at Top of World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Sportswriter Liu Guang and Duoji Zhandui
</P>
<P>
LHASA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The holy flame of the sixth
national ethnic games, which was collected from the "top of the
world" Mountain Qomolangma, lit up the whole stadium and the faces
of RigNa and GiGi.
</P>
<P>
After becoming one of the three Chinese climbers who conquered
10 mountains standing over 8,000 meters high, RigNa made his mark
again with his wife by becoming the first couple to scale the
seemingly invincible Mt. Qomolangma.
</P>
<P>
The couple, together with the other 8 members including another
female climber, have completed the feat of gathering the tinder
from Mt. Qomolangma for the sixth national ethnic games which
kicked off on Wednesday here.
</P>
<P>
The suffering during his odyssey was indelible in RigNa's
memory although he has been an old mariner since he begun his
climbing career 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
"The life out there was hard. Our dinner time was very casual
and we often trekked for seven or eight hours running. We can only
feed ourselves with chocolate and biscuit."
</P>
<P>
"We will also be liable to altitude illness and felt sick to
anything edible. But we had to take in food no matter how much
antipathy we had to food."
</P>
<P>
"When we arrived at the 6,500 meters line, the most serious
altitude sickness often happened, such as a very bad headache and
the state of being dog exhausted."
</P>
<P>
"But we could not sit or lie down, for this would further
consume our physical power and made us going forward more
difficult. So we just rested our head on the walking stick while
keeping standing poise. "
</P>
<P>
"Our brain will be in a mess and lost sleep at the 7,900 meter
line, and beyond that it would be counted as a great feat if we
managed ten straight steps in one breath."
</P>
<P>
Dangerous and hard as the climb was, RigNa did not beat the
retreat drum.
</P>
<P>
"I just tried something that has not been tested." said the 32-
year-old Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
GiGi, 29, who was the first time to climb Mt. Qomolangma,
talked as if it just happened yesterday.
</P>
<P>
"Mountain climbing is very hard. After arriving at the climax
my excitedness was temporary and we were soon preoccupied with
solitude on how to get down in safety."
</P>
<P>
"But I still felt quite honored to shoulder the significant
task of climbing Mt. Qomolangma for kindling material." said GiGi
who escorted the flame torch on the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"This time though we could not take part in the national ethnic
games competition, but I still feel quite honored to attend the
opening ceremony." said GiGi. "In the future if there are chances
I will continue to climb and climb."
</P>
<P>
GiGi lost her sleep on the eve of a 17-hour non-stop trekking
during which she eat nothing and crossed over the climax before
they got down to the ABC (advance Base Camp) at the 6500 meters
line.
</P>
<P>
RigNa gave his wife encouragement while the difficulty had
hardly knock down Gigi, who was the youngest female athlete in the
Tibetan mountain climbing team.
</P>
<P>
"When she suffered altitude illness and felt sick to food, I
required her to eat, otherwise she could not reach the top. And I
tried to care about her on the way for I am much experienced,
knowing how to make precautionary measures against the accidents,
and I am much stronger so that I can recover my physical power
faster than her."
</P>
<P>
To RigNa's great comfort was the strong will of GiGi who was a
long and middle distance runner before she joined the Tibetan
mountain climbing team in 1989.
</P>
<P>
RigNa said that no matter how hard the conditions were, she had
never kneel down before the hardship even when they got a piece of
bad news that three foreign expedition teams, who started in
advance, suffered one death and one serious injury respectively.
</P>
<P>
The couple have never flinched in their expedition but they
showed their paternal side when saying goodbye to their five-year-
old daughter Lhamo Yangchen.
</P>
<P>
GiGi said that at the farewell ceremony to the Mt. Qomolangma
expedition she hid herself inside the crossfield car for she had
no guts to face her daughter and feared seeing the tears on her
face.
</P>
<P>
Crying Lhamo Yangchen broke away from the relatives to hug
tight his father whose tears trickled down the face of Lhamo
Yangchen.
</P>
<P>
During the trekking, GiGi heard the sweet and crisp voice of
Lhamo Yangchen through the satellite telephone but she could not
utter one word before RigNa picked up the call.
</P>
<P>
"Is mother crying? why did she not talk with me?" the innocent
Lhamo Yangchen asked on the other end of the line.
</P>
<P>
"No, No, she is quite well, " RigNa tried to paper it over
although his eyes had been teary.
</P>
<P>
Both RigNa and GiGi are reluctant to let their daughter to
follow their footsteps for "the mountain climbing is too hard and
dangerous."
</P>
<P>
"But if she is persistent in taking upon the enterprise, we
would not stop her." said the parents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Boost Cotton Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government has
decided to encourage domestic economic sectors to boost cotton
production in order to reduce cotton imports, Vietnam news agency
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a decision issued Tuesday, Prime Minister Phan Van Khai said
that establishments and individuals of all economic sectors are
encouraged to develop production of cotton in areas where there
are favorable conditions in terms of soil, climate and labor.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam imports 50,000-60,000 tons of cotton fiber a year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development will
coordinate with the People's Committees of cotton-growing
provinces and the Vietnam Garments and Textiles Corporation in
forming concentrated cotton-growing areas, applying intensive
farming technique.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam expanded cotton-growing areas to 24,000 hectares in
1998 with an average yield of 890 kg per hectare. It plans to
further expand the areas to 100,000 hectare by 2010 with an
estimated yield of 1.8 tons per hectare, thus meeting some 25
percent of its textile industry's needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
