<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Water Supplies Still in Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot water storage in
reservoirs nearly doubled in August compared with the
corresponding period last year, but still fell far short of the
needed volume.
</P>
<P>
The latest report from the Cypriot Water Development Department
(WDD) showed that there are 47.1 million cubic meters of water
behind the dams, 20.7 million cubic meters more than in August
1998, the Cyprus Mail newspaper said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to WDD, Cyprus needs 57 million cubic meters of water
for domestic use every year and 81 million cubic meters more for
irrigation.
</P>
<P>
Last year's drought has prompted the government to announce
that three more desalination plants were on the way to ease the
water shortage.
</P>
<P>
But the arrival of winter rains convinced the government that
maybe there was no need to rush ahead with the costly desalination
plants.
</P>
<P>
Besides, repeated protests of local residents who were unhappy
with the idea of building desalination plants in their
neighborhoods also played a part in government's change of its
mind.
</P>
<P>
The contract for a second permanent desalination plant in
Larnaca area has been signed. But the future of the two proposed
mobile desalination plants remains uncertain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
