<HEADLINE> New Record Tourism Income Expected in 1999 in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus is expecting a better
holiday season this year, with the latest figure projecting a new
record income of 1 billion Cyprus pounds (2 billion U.S. dollars)
from tourism for 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the Cyprus Tourism Organization (CTO), arrivals
in the first six months of this year have increased by 10 percent
from last year's record number in the same period, the Cyprus Mail
newspaper reported Thursday. The per capita spending is also up by
7 percent, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Cyprus earned record 880 million pounds (1,760
million dollars) from tourism and this year the receipts are
expected to reach 1 billion pounds (2 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
"The income from tourism has increased by a total 17 percent
for the past six months, which is a very encouraging
development," CTO Director of Tourism Phoebe Katsouris said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
She estimated that overall arrivals for the year will increase
by 7 percent from last year's 2.2 million.
</P>
<P>
Foreign visitors flocked to Cyprus not only in greater numbers,
but their average stay has also risen to an average 11.2 days from
10.5 days, which partly contributed to the increase in spending
per head. "The amount spent per day per person has risen by 1.2
percent," Katsouris said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
