<HEADLINE> Jordan to Be Oil Exporter in 10 Years: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Jordan has attracted local and
foreign investments in billions of dollars for oil and energy
development and will be an oil exporter in 10 years, ending
decades of oil imports from neighbor countries.
</P>
<P>
The prediction was made by Energy Minister Suleiman Abu Ileim
in an interview with the Jordanian weekly newspaper Star which was
published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Suleiman said after years of exploration, shale oil has been
found in southeastern and central Jordan, which holds about 40
billion tons of shale oil that is capable of producing 20 billion
tons of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
He said Jordan hoped to produce 250,000 tons of shale oil
annually by the year 2007 and the kingdom will be oil
self-sufficient before it becomes an oil exporter within the next
10 years.
</P>
<P>
Suleiman said local and foreign investments in shale oil
exploration and production have reached 2.4 billion dollars under
his ministry`s ambitious strategy to find out new energy
resources.
</P>
<P>
Another 1 billion dollars of foreign investments were attracted
to boost gas production of the kingdom, he added.
</P>
<P>
Currently Jordan totally depends on Iraq for crude oil,
importing 70,000 tons from each day from Baghdad under the
U.N. oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Jordan produces 15,000 tons of oil products every day from the
crude oil imports from Iraq, and 40 percent of the products were
used for generating electricity.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia suspended its oil supply to Jordan after Iraq's
invasion of Kuwait in 1990 because Amman sided with Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
