<HEADLINE> Uganda, Rwanda Appoint New Officers to Kisangani </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Rwanda have agreed to
appoint new officers to Kisangani in the Democratic Republic of
the Congo (DRC) where their two armed forces have been fighting
each other since last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's Army Commander Jeje Odongo and his Rwandan counterpart
 Brigadier Kayumba were appointed to take charge in Kisangani, the
third largest city in the DRC, the New Vision paper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan army Chief of Staff James Kazini and his Rwandan
counterpart James Kabarebe, who had been heading the two
countries' military operations in the DRC, were ordered to report
the situation there to Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and
Rwandan Vice President and Minister of Defense Paul Kagame
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The four-day clashes between the two armed troops over the
control of Kisangani left over 60 people dead, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Museveni and Kagame met in western Uganda early this week and
agreed on a ceasefire Tuesday afternoon to revive their
five-year-long military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Both Uganda and Rwanda are backing the rebel movement against
DRC President Laurent Kabila. Their strategic and tactic
differences prompted them to support rival factions of the rebel
group after it split into two in mid-May. 
</P>
