<HEADLINE> Old Gold, Silver Ingots Discovered in Northwestern Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A gold ingot and a silver one that
were made 1,300 years ago were recently dug up in the northwestern
Chinese city of Xi'an during construction work at a middle school.
</P>
<P>
The ingots were turned over to the local cultural relics
department. The gold ingot is 15 cm by three cm by one cm and
weighs 414 grams. It is stamped with the characters for "tribute
gold from Yaozhou", referring to an area in Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
The silver ingot is larger and weighs 2,250 grams. It bears the
characters for "tribute silver from Raozhou", referring to Jiangxi
Province. Both ingots date back to the reign of Empress Wu Zetian
during the Tang Dynasty (618-907), the only woman in Chinese
history to proclaim herself sovereign.  
</P>
