<HEADLINE> Newspaper: South Korea to Cut Military Size by 2015 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 19 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will phase its
reductions in armed forces from the current 690,000 to 400,000-500,
000 by the year 2015 in the hope of the peninsula's peaceful
reunification, the local newspaper Dong-A Ilbo reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The defense authority plans to cut the size of the military on
long-term expectations of the unification of the Korean peninsula
and "an atmosphere of peaceful co-existence," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
A defense ministry spokesman confirmed to Xinhua Thursday that
the ministry does have a disarmament plan, but giving no specific
figures.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper report said the proportion of officers would be
raised from the present 24 percent to over 30 percent by 2015,
while the ratio of the army to the entire military force would be
reduced from 81.2 percent to 71 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the defense ministry would strengthen military
intelligence and precision attack power as it believes security in
northeast Asia will still be affected by uncertain factors in the
21st century, the paper said. 
