<HEADLINE> Five-working-day Week to Be Implemented in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 19 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government decided
to adopt a five-working-day week in the Kathmandu Valley starting
from August 22, working hours will be 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. during
summer and 9 a.m. to 4 p.m. during the four winter months, The
Kathmandu Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The new move is estimated to save the government 120 million
rupees (1.7 million U.S. dollars) in expense every year. The
reduce of the working days in a week will also help slow down
traffic and environmental pollution.
</P>
<P>
The new arrangement will be expanded to other parts of Nepal in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
However, Nepal Freight Forwarders' Association, the main medium
for export-import business of Nepal, said in the press release
that since the government took this decision without concerning
export-import related organizations, the prospectus may be fatal
in future.
</P>
<P>
The agencies related to export such as Tribhuvan International
Airport, Customs Office, Chamber of Commerce and Industry,
Department of Archeology, Handicrafts Association of Nepal, Carpet
and Wool Development Committee, Garment Visa Section, Central
Carpet Industry Association, Nepal Garment Association ion and
commercial banks should cater their service throughout the week,
said the press release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
