<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, India to Carry Cargo on 50-50 Basis in Riverine Transit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and India have agreed
to carry cargo by the vessels of the two countries on a 50-50
basis in the riverine transit provided by Dhaka, The Independent
daily newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides singed an agreed minute here on Wednesday at the
end of a two-day meeting of a joint working group of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The working group, comprising officials of both sides at the
level of the joint secretary, was formed in 1997 to find out
modalities for rational implementation of the riverine transit
protocol, which was singed in 1947 between India and then Pakistan
and is being renewed every two years.
</P>
<P>
The agreed minute on the transportation of cargo by vessels of
the two countries would be included in the riverine transit
protocol to be renewed at a scheduled meeting in Dhaka on
September 15 after the approval by the two governments, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The new arrangement would enable Bangladesh to earn from the
cargo transportation business instead of India's one-sided
benefits.
</P>
<P>
Joint Secretary of the Shipping Ministry M. Abdul Huq said the
meeting was held in a "cordial and friendly atmosphere" and the
two sides agreed to find out modalities on the transportation of
cargo by the vessels of the two countries on a 50-50 basis.
</P>
<P>
Authorities in Bangladesh and India would undertake quarterly
review and monitoring on the carrying of cargo by the vessels of
both countries on a 50-50 basis, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
A report in The Financial Express daily said that under the
provision of the riverine transit protocol, both inter-country and
transit cargoes are to be carried by vessels of the two countries
on a 50-50 basis, but this could not be implemented due to
indifferent attitude of the Indian port authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Forest Cover Lowers in Nepal: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A study conducted by the
government says Nepal's forest area has come down to 29 percent
from 37.4 percent in the 1980's, The Kathmandu Post reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report, however, is yet to be adopted, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the Ministry of Forest and Soil Conservation (MFSC)
said there has been a 10 percent rise in the country's shrubland
area, indicating that forest cover has dwindled significantly.
Shrubland area was five percent 10 year ago.
</P>
<P>
It may be said that densely forested areas with over 10 percent
crown cover are categorized as forests while those with less than
10 percent crown cover are considered as shrubland.
</P>
<P>
A study conducted in the 1980's had put Nepal's forest,
grassland and shrubland areas at 37.4, 12 and 5 percent
respectively, while the average annual deforestation rate stood at
1.1 percent. Deforestation rate in the Terai Plain in southern
Nepal was 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Experts have predicted desertification and unprecedented
environmental disaster if the present trend is not curbed on time.
They said forest cover should occupy at least 43 percent of land
area to maintain environmental balance.
</P>
<P>
Forest cover in Nepal stood at 45 percent until the late
sixties when the tract of land separating the Terai Plain and the
hills was not cleared by settlers from the hilly regions.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the deforestation are attributed to the negligence
of the government over forest conservation and rampant logging
along with population boom. 
</P>
