<HEADLINE> China Urges U.S. to Take Concrete Actions Before Resuming WTO Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 19 (Xinhua) -- China urges the United States to
take more concrete actions to improve bilateral relations and pave
the way for a resumption of negotiations in China's entry into the
World Trade Organization (WTO), a spokesman said here Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Hu Chusheng, spokesman for the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), said at a press conference that the
current standstill in WTO talks is "totally because of reasons of
the U.S. side."
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the U.S. side would take more concrete actions to
improve Sino-US relations, so that conditions would be created for
a resumption of the talks in China's entry into the WTO."
</P>
<P>
He said that important progress was scored during the latest
round of bilateral talks with a dozen countries in Geneva not long
ago. He described the talks as "constructive."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that China has never changed its
attitude and stance in its bid to enter the multilateral trade
body, and the negotiation process has never been suspended.
</P>
<P>
China's efforts to join WTO and its predecessor has lasted for
13 years. Important progress was achieved during Chinese Premier
Zhu Rongji's visit to the United States in the bilateral talks
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
But negotiations between China and the United States virtually
stopped following the U.S.-led NATO's missile attack on Chinese
embassy in Belgrade last May.
</P>
<P>
Last month, China and Japan, Australia announced respectively
that they have completed bilateral talks on China's WTO entry.
</P>
</TEXT>
