<HEADLINE> Agassi Cruises But Chang Upset at Legg Mason Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Andre Agassi trounced Sweden'
s Mikael Tillstrom 6-1, 6-1 in the second round of the $600,000
Legg Mason tennis hardcourt event here tonight.
</P>
<P>
The second-seeded American dazzled with sharp ground strokes
and an efficiant serve to post a 50-minute victory.
</P>
<P>
"I'm going to sleep well tonight," joked Agassi, who won 78
percent of his service points. "I'm hitting the ball well. A match
like this is good for your confidence and good for your next match.
"
</P>
<P>
Two seeds went by the wayside, including two-time winner
Michael Chang of the United States. The 13th seed fell to Ramond
Delgado of Paraguay 4-6, 6-1, 3-6 in his final tune-up before the
U.S. Open, which is two weeks away.
</P>
<P>
"This is not what I wanted," Chang said. "It's irratating today.
I won the second set comfortably and in the third I was able to
fight my way back. I would have liked to win a few more matches
before the Open."
</P>
<P>
A four-time winner and defending champion here, Agassi has won
24 of his last 28 matches, including the French Open in June.
Agassi next faces 19-year-old Bjorn Phau of Germany, who rallied
past Italy's Laurence Tieleman 3-6, 6-3, 6-4, earlier today.
</P>
<P>
Four seeds also advanced to the third round. No. 5 Alex
Corretja of Spain won for just the second time in his last five
matches by getting past Gianluca Pozzi of Italy 7-6 (7-5), 1-6, 7-
5.
</P>
<P>
Seventh seed Marc Rosset of Switzerland won 70 percent of his
service points to beat Fernando Gonzalez of Chile 7-6 (11-9), 6-4;
ninth seed Fabrice Santoro of France beat Ronald Agenor of Haiti 6-
4, 6-4; and No. 14 Jan Kroslak of Slovakia subdued Lorenzo Manta
of Switzerland 7-5, 7-6 (7-3).
</P>
<P>
Tenth seed Rainer Schuttler of Germany suffered cramps in his
arms and legs before retiring from his match against Tomas Zib of
the Czech Republic, who was leading 6-7 (2-7), 7-5, 3-0. 
</P>
