<HEADLINE> EDS-rpt with correction in 3rd para Bosnia Urged to Step Up Implementation of Dayton Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The international community's new
high representative to Bosnia Wednesday urged Bosnian leaders to
step up the implementation of the Dayton Peace Accord and to fight
the reportedly-rampant corruption among government officials.
</P>
<P>
Wolfgang Petritsch made the call at his first press conference
in the Bosnian capital of Sarajevo after he succeeded Spanish
diplomat Carlos Westendorp as the international community's new
envoy to Bosnia earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Petritsch, quoted by reports reaching here, said that Bosnian
leaders should make serious efforts so that the goals of the
accord are fully achieved. The accord was signed four years ago to
end the four-year Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian diplomat said he will not tolerate extremists and
nationalists and that if necessary, he will use various powers
granted him, including the power to remove Bosnian officials.
</P>
<P>
As for corruption, Petritsch said corruption was an important
topic during his first meeting with Alijia Izetbegovic, member of
Bosnia-Herzegovina's presidency, since he took the post.
</P>
<P>
Graft, bribery and embezzlement of public funds are a realistic
problem in Bosnia, which is distancing the country from the
European Union (EU), Petritsch said.
</P>
<P>
Wiping out corruption in Bosnia is a top priority for the
Office of the High Representative, he said.
</P>
<P>
Petritsch has served as Austria's ambassador to Belgrade and as
the EU's special representative for Kosovo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
