<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin, Dalian Ports Report Record Cargo Handling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin port, the largest in
north China, handled 41.29 million tons of cargo and 708,000 TEUs
in the first seven months this year, a record high that was 4.5
and 30.6 percent more than the same period last year, respectively.
</P>
<P>
In northeast China, Dalian port also reported an all-time high
in cargo it handled during the first half of this year. The port
handled 41.07 million tons of goods in the six months, an increase
of 16 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total cargo handled by Tianjin port, import and export
goods increased by 805,000 tons, or 3.91 percent, compared with a
year earlier, while goods for domestic trade rose by 981,000 tons,
or 5.18 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that the increase indicated a recovery of
China's trade with other parts of the world and of its domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
Statistics provided by the Tianjin port administration show
that the goods handled in the seven months included 835,000 tons
of refined oil, up 51.5 percent year on year; 2.54 million tons of
crude oil, up 33.6 percent; and 1.05 million tons of imported
fertilizer, up 24.3 percent. Meanwhile coke and coal handled by
the port decreased by a big margin, with imported grain down 14.4
percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
To expand its handling capacity, Tianjin port invested in the
past seven months nearly 300 million yuan (36 million U.S. dollars)
in infrastructure construction, and total investment is expected
to top 900 million yuan for the year.
</P>
<P>
According to port officials, a 35,000-ton dock for nonmetal
minerals will be put into operation by the end of this year at
Tianjin port, while a 50,000-ton coke dock and a 35,000-ton dock
and another 50,000-ton coal dock are expected to go into operation
next June.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-15 Ministers Call For Implementation Of Existing Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 19 (Xinhua) -- G-15 countries Wednesday
rejected attempts by industrialized nations to erect non-trade
barriers under the garb of new trade issues and resolved to press
for implementation of existing agreements of the World Trade
Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
At the end of a two-day conference in Bangalore, south India,
trade ministers of the G-15 developing countries unanimously
opposed linkage of social clauses with trade and registered a
protest against moves by developed countries to bring in anything
that would result in prevent market access to developing nations.
</P>
<P>
According to Press Trust of India (PTI), the ministers
recognized three facets of implementation issues and concerns
relating to removal of inequities in the existing agreements,
non-realization of benefits by several developing nations and
special and differential provisions in the Uruguay Round
agreements that have remained unimplemented.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the press in Bangalore on Wednesday, Indian Commerce
Minister Ramakrishna Hedge said that there was a sense of unity
among the member states and a new awareness of the pitfalls ahead
if developing countries rushed in for fresh trade negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Hedge said that there was a need for G-15 countries to adopt a
mutually-supported position through their permanent
representatives in Geneva to ensure that corrective measures were
taken by the scheduled WTO ministerial meeting in November in
Seattle, the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Indian minister said that all the delegations disfavored
overloading of the Seattle agenda and many felt that mandated
negotiations and reviews must constitute the core agenda, though
some were prepared for limited add-ones like tariff negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held in accordance with the decision of the
trade ministers of the group last February at Montego Bay,
Jamaica, to evolve a coordinated approach to issues likely to come
up at the Seattle conference.
</P>
<P>
However, there are signs of differences among member countries
at the meeting, which issued only a chairman's summary.
</P>
<P>
Clarifying that the summary was not in the form of a
resolution, Hedge said that it reflected the views of the member
states and the kind of consensus that was reached among the 17
countries presented at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reaffirmed its commitment to rule-based and
equitable multilateral trading systems resulting in the full
integration of developing countries into the systems for their
economic development and global trade expansion.
</P>
<P>
The delegates noted the need for institutional reforms and
greater transparency in the dispute settlement proceedings of the
WTO and observed that dispute settlement was a process undertaken
between two governments and therefore required very strict
confidentiality at all stages.
</P>
<P>
They urged the ministers at Seattle to clearly recognize that
environmental standards differed from nation to nation and that
the solution lay in mutual recognition of only product-related
standards rather than harmonization of environmental standards.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Egypt, the current G-15 chairman, asked developing
countries not to allow their differing interests to "obscure"
their vision during the forthcoming WTO ministerial meeting in
which developed nations were expected to attempt to erect
non-trade barriers by raising new issues.
</P>
<P>
Hedge admitted Tuesday that G-15 members might differ on issues
as they were at various stages of development.
</P>
<P>
G-15 came into being during the 9he Non-Aligned Summit in
Belgrade in September 1989, with the intention to create a
functional and compact group of developing countries that could
focus on South-South economic cooperation supported by political
engagement at the highest level.
</P>
<P>
With a combined gross domestic product of over two trillion
U.S. dollars and a trade turnover of 600 billion U.S. dollars,
annual export growth in these countries continued to linger around
4.3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Funds Injected into Rural Infrastructure In Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- A total of 2.16 billion pesos
(54 million U.S. dollars) in funds sourced from foreign donors has
been invested in various rural infrastructure projects by the
Philippine government for the first quarter of 1999 alone.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Horacio Morales, Jr. of the Department of Agrarian
Reform (DAR) said the amount represents more than half of the 3.76
billion pesos (94 million dollars) of the DAR's foreign assisted
physical infrastructure fund for the year.
</P>
<P>
The DAR hopes to provide infrastructure and support services to
710 regions, benefiting close to 600,000 farmer beneficiaries,
Philippine News Agency quoted Morales as saying.
</P>
<P>
The completed projects include irrigation servicing an area of
more than 2,000 hectares, 229 kilometers of farm-to-market roads,
108 linear meters of bridges, 90 water systems, 47
pre-and-post-harvest facilities, and 20.7 kilometers of rural
electrification. Beneficiaries to these projects are 158 regions.
</P>
<P>
A total of 396 other infrastructure projects would be
implemented this year in support of the agricultural modernization
and food security, Morales added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
