<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Coach Pat Riley Agrees to Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Miami Heat coach Pat Riley
Wednesday reached a mutual agreement with owner Micky Arison to
trigger an extension clause in his contract that will keep him
with the team into the 21st century," according to a local report.
</P>
<P>
No terms were disclosed. Riley was entering the final year of a
five-year, $40 million contract he signed in 1995, when he left
the New York Knicks under unpleasant circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Riley, 54, is second on the NBA's all-time coaching wins list
and first in playoff wins. He won four championships as coach of
the Los Angeles Lakers, guided the Knicks to an appearance in the
NBA Finals and has turned Miami into a perennial contender.
</P>
<P>
"I want to thank Micky Arison for his support and belief that I
can get the job done," Riley said. "We have much to do in the
coming years, with our main objective forever and always being the
building of a championship team.
</P>
<P>
"My family and I have fallen in love with Miami and we hope
that this will be the final destination of a long coaching journey,
" Riley added.
</P>
<P>
Riley is 191-105 since taking over the Heat. He has guided the
team to three Atlantic Division titles and a trip to the Eastern
Conference finals in 1997. However, Miami has been eliminated by
New York in the first round of the playoffs in each of the last
two seasons.
</P>
<P>
As the executive with final say on all personnel moves, Riley
has swung deals for All-Stars Alonzo Mourning and Tim Hardaway.
This offseason, he signed forward Otis Thorpe away from the
Washington Wizzards and re-signed swingman Dan Majerle.
</P>
<P>
Riley never has missed the playoffs in 17 years as a coach. He
won NBA titles with the Lakers in 1982, 1985, 1987 and 1988. He
spent a one-season hiatus as a TV analyst and returned to coaching
with the Knicks in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Under Riley, New York lost to Houston in the 1994 NBA Finals.
The following year, the Knicks lost in the conference semifinals
and Riley was vilified by the New York media for resigning his
post via fax. He still draws among the loudest boos of any visitor
to Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
With an all-time record of 947-404, Riley trails only Atlanta
coach Lenny Wilkens on the all-time wins list. His 149 playoff
wins are unsurpassed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
