<HEADLINE> Argentine, Chilean Presidents to Inaugurate Gas Pipeline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Chilean President Eduardo
Frei will travel to Argentina on Thursday to join his host
President Carlos Menem at the inauguration of a gas pipeline that
will transport gas from Argentina to Chile.
</P>
<P>
It cost 850 million U.S. dollars to build the 941-kilometer gas
pipeline, which has the capacity to carry 8.5 million cubic meters
of gas per day.
</P>
<P>
Both countries regard the joint project as important to their
economies. Argentina will use the gas for the development of its
mining and industrial zone in addition to home gas supply, while
Chile will use the gas in thermal power plants to generate
electricity. Chile also has plans to extend the pipeline to other
cities in the north.
</P>
<P>
The inaugural ceremony will be held first in the Argentine
province of Jujuy and then in Mejillones, Chile. The two
presidents will afterwards travel to Santiago of Chile, where
President Menem is expected to stay until Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
