<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Allocate Bonuses for SEA Games Athletes, Coaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Despite a poor performance in
Brunei's 20th Southeast Asian (SEA) Games, the Indonesian Sports
Council (KONI) still intends to keep its promise to allocate
bonuses for its high achieving athletes and coaches.
</P>
<P>
KONI Secretary General Rudolf Warouw confirmed the plan. He
said the federation had previously set aside funds in its budget
for the country's sporting ambassadors who are able to bring home
medals.
</P>
<P>
As in previous years, all participants will receive an
insurance package, he was quoted by The Indonesian Observer
Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Warouw however declined to mention details, including the exact
figure, saying that the matter is still being assessed by the
federation.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia went through a bad spell in last week's sporting
showcase, not only failing to retain the overall trophy, but also
contending with its worst case scenario becoming a reality, that
is, being surpassed by Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia pocketed an overall 44 gold medals -- which is a far
cry from the haul of 194 bagged by Indonesia in the 1997 SEA Games
-- to end the nightmare in third spot.
</P>
<P>
It was Indonesia's worst feat ever in 22 years of participation
in the biennial tournament.
</P>
<P>
The failure of the Indonesian contingent was reported to the
president during a limited cabinet meeting here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Sport and Youth Affairs Minister Agung Laksono reported to
President B.J. Habibie that Indonesia managed to grab only 44
golds, which are below the projected to 70-75 golds," Information
Minister Muhammad Yunus said.
</P>
<P>
However, several Indonesian athletes broke SEA Games records in
track and field and swimming, Yunus said.
</P>
<P>
The current prolonged economic crisis is seen as a factor
behind the country's breakdown in the 1999 SEA Games in Brunei
Darussalam, Yunus said, adding that the crisis curbed the
government's capacity to fund the development of sports in the
country.
</P>
<P>
"The economic problems had also forced private companies to
reduce their financial support," he was quoted by the Antara News
Agency Thursday as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
