<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elliott Family Meets Media for First time Since Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Two days after transplant
recipient Sean Elliott received his brother's kidney, the family
of the San Antonio Spurs forward met the media today at the
Methodist Specialty and Transplant Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Noel Elliott, who donated the kidney to his brother, reported
he was feeling good, although suffering through occasional
discomfort.
</P>
<P>
"I've been hanging out, trying to get up and walk around," he
said. "That's the hardest part so far."
</P>
<P>
What was never hard was the decision to help his brother. Upon
learning he was a viable donor, Noel Elliott never hesitated to
offer the life-saving organ.
</P>
<P>
"It's something I would have done for either of my brothers,"
Noel Elliott said. "For Sean and myself, I was a good match. My
other brother was ruled out as a match.
</P>
<P>
"I'm kind of an instant celebrity. I want to encourage anyone
who's on the edge of being a donor to seriously consider donating
an organ or bone marrow or anything they can donate, whether it's
blood or organs."
</P>
<P>
An outpouring of support prompted Sean Elliott to complain
about his lack of access to the Internet in order to sift through
the well wishes of supporter. He could check no e-mail while in
the intensive care until Monday but was transferred to a regular
room on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
His mother, Odiemae, thanked all of those who called, prayed
and wished her sons well, adding she could never manage to
acknowledge all the supporters.
</P>
<P>
"I had two sons in the operating room at one time," she said. "
Are you looking for the tears? It's been a long journey. It's been
seven years for Sean that we've known he was as well as he could
be. This summer, I had to face reality and there could be no more
denial.
</P>
<P>
Sean Elliott has been taking heavy doses of medicine to limit
the chances of rejection of the organ by his body.
</P>
<P>
Noel Elliott had a donor procedure that now is less intrusive
than such operations in the past. A smaller incision is made in
extracting the kidney, thus speeding the healing process,
particularly after a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Francis Wright, who was the surgeon on the transplant, said
Sean Elliott's activity has been limited, but the prognosis
continues to be good.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the surgery, Wright never ruled out the
possibility the player might return to the NBA. Today, Noel
Elliott concurred with Wright's sentiments.
</P>
<P>
"I hope he will be able to get back to where he wants to be,"
Noel Elliott said. "If he wants to play next season."
</P>
<P>
Sean Elliott, 31, played with kidney disease for the last few
years but significant deterioration of the renal function over the
last 12 months led to Monday's surgery. He has indicated no
retirement plans, although his return for the 1999-2000 season
still is considered highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
Elliott played in all of San Antonio's 17 playoff games this
year and averaged 11.9 points, 3.4 rebounds and 2.7 assists in a
15-2 postseason run. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
