<HEADLINE> Violence Increases in Colombia, Eight More Villagers Killed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Violence is increasing
in Colombia as suspected right-wing paramilitary gunmen on
Wednesday killed eight more villagers in the Curumani region,
north of the country.
</P>
<P>
Local radio quoted the witnesses as saying that the assassins
described the victims as collaborators of the left-wing guerrillas,
warning others of "the same fate" if they support the leftists.
</P>
<P>
The atrocity occurred several hours after gunmen killed at
least 13 people late Tuesday and dumped their bodies along a
highway.
</P>
<P>
In another development on Wednesday, a bomb exploded in the
entrance of a bakery in the northeastern city of Cucuta, leaving
two people wounded. No group has yet claimed responsibility for
the incident.
</P>
<P>
In the province of Norte de Santander, authorities meanwhile
deactivated a car bomb for which they blamed the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
According to Colombia's federal human rights ombudsman, 847
civilians have died in massacres so far this year, up 44 percent
from 1998.
</P>
<P>
Majority of the dead have been killed as suspected leftist
sympathizers. The gunmen are reported to be financed by drug
traffickers and wealthy landowners. 
</P>
