<HEADLINE> Foreign Travelers to Czech Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 45 million foreigners
traveled to the Czech republic in the first six months of 1999,
which is 6.4 percent fewer compared with the same period in 1998,
Czech's State Statistics Bureau reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 20 percent fewer foreign tourists arrived
in April compared to the same period in the previous year. In the
meantime, Czech's domestic travelers going abroad reached 17.9
million, a 10.4 percent decrease compared with the same period
during the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the tourism sector attribute the decline to NATO's
78-day bombing of Yugoslavia. They said that since the end of
NATO's war against Serbians in Kosovo, a great number of foreign
tourists, fearing the danger of war, have canceled their programs
to visit the country. 
</P>
