<HEADLINE> Survey: Most Austrians Against NATO Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The majority of Austrians insist
that their country stay neutral in world affairs and stay away
from the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), according to a
survey released here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Over two thirds of Austrians believe "keeping neutral is still
an integral part of Austria's foreign and security policy," and 54
percent think that Austria should remain neutral, not join NATO
or any other European security alliance.
</P>
<P>
Only 16 percent support Austria's NATO membership, according to
polls sponsored by the European Policy Association of Austria.
</P>
<P>
Around 71 percent of Austrians believe their country will not
be threatened by any other country's military force in the near
future, said the survey.
</P>
<P>
The polls also found that many Austrians, especially the under-
educated, do not care about their country's security policy and do
not know the pros and cons of joining NATO. However, they think
Austria should remain neutral because the Constitution stipulates
permanent neutrality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
