<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Garment Factory Workers Face Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Over 100,000 Sri Lankan garment
factory workers will face unemployment, according to reports of
the Island newspaper Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They are employees of factories set up under the 200 Garment
Factory Program located outside the investment promotion zones,
which the Board of Investment (BOI) has decided not to service.
</P>
<P>
Recently the BOI informed them of the decision and has asked
them to obtain facilities from the Customs department.
</P>
<P>
The affected investors claim that this is in violation of the
agreements reached by them at the time of investment and for
taking resources into remote areas, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Investors say that the recent negative growth of the industry
was as a result of obstacles such as this that they had to face.
They add that government has promised them a "one stop shop" to
encourage them to go to the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
If government was not interested in developing the rural areas
they could operate more comfortably in the Zones.
</P>
<P>
They have described the new directive as outright
discrimination against investors who have gone to the rural areas
for the sake of rural development.
</P>
<P>
Nearly fifty investors, affected by the new decision, have
challenged the BOI ruling not to service them, the reports added.
 
</P>
