<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wizards Agree to Terms with Mitch Richmond </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Washington Wizards
Wednesday agreed in principle to a contract with All-Star guard
Mitch Richmond, who was the team's leading scorer during the
abbreviated 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
No financial terms or length of the deal were disclosed, but
ESPN, citing no official sources, reported on Tuesday that the
contract is for four years at $40 million.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post, citing an unidentified source close to the
negotiations, has reported the Wizards can buy out the six-time
All-Star for $10 million after two years and $5 million after
three years.
</P>
<P>
With an annual average of $10 million, the contract makes the
34-year-old Richmond the NBA's highest-paid shooting guard. Guards
Latrell Sprewell, Allen Iverson, Kobe Bryant and Reggie Miller all
have deals paying them in the $9 million range next season.
</P>
<P>
Richmond led the Wizards with 19.7 points per game last season,
it was the lowest average of his 10-year career.
</P>
<P>
The reported deal is similar to the one the Wizards struck
prior to last season with Rod Strickland. The point guard signed a
four-year, $40 million deal which has a $5 million buyout after
the third season.
</P>
<P>
Richmond was a 1988 first-round pick of the Golden State
Warriors. In May 1998, he was acquired with Otis Thorpe for Chris
Webber from the Sacramento Kings, for whom he spent seven seasons.
He has played in only 21 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
Richmond was the 1989 Rookie of the Year and 1995 All-Star Game
Most Valuable Player. Prior to last season, he never averaged less
than 21.9 points per game, with a high of 25.9 in 1996-97.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
