<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Seizes 8.6 Tons of Cocaine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 18 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican government
Wednesday announced the seizure of 8.6 tons of cocaine in
international waters, with the help of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Mexican General Attorney Jorge Madrazo said that the
confiscation of the cocaine, the largest amount this decade,
occurred on Saturday aboard a fishing boat carrying the Mexican
flag after an alert was received from the U.S. Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
The captain of the boat and 15 crew members were detained at
the Mexican port of Lazaro Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
Madrazo said that after reinforcing the border patrol, 25 tons
of cocaine, 850 tons of marijuana and 671 tons of opium gum have
been seized during the past 8 months.
</P>
<P>
The drug, which is believed to have come from Colombia, will be
destroyed in the next few hours, authorities said. It is not known
which of the drug "Cartels" was behind this shipment.
</P>
<P>
Madrazo also said that in the campaign against drug trafficking,
in cooperation with the U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency (DEA) and the
Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), they have delivered strong
and direct hits to the drug "Cartels." 
</P>
</TEXT>
