<HEADLINE> Australia's One Nation Party Leaders Face Fraud Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 19 (Xinhua) --A court ruling pushes Australian
notorious One Nation party into its downhill path.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the Canberra Times Thursday, the
party's registration in Queensland state was sentenced Wednesday
to be invalid.
</P>
<P>
It was found in the supreme court that One Nation's
registration as a political party in Queensland had been induced
by fraud and misrepresentation because the party did not have as
many members as it professed to.
</P>
<P>
A Sydney businessman Chuck Hong was quoted as saying Wednesday
that he would launch similar court action against the party in the
New South Wales state believing there had been electoral fraud
also.
</P>
<P>
The party's leadership team, including Pauline Hanson, may face
fraud charges as a result of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
The penalty for electoral fraud is up to six months' jail in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
One Nation party, established in 1997, is believed widely to be
hostile to the Australian Aboriginals and Asian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Upholding its nationalist, if not racist flag, the party won a
shining victory in Queensland in last year's general election by
taking 11 seats in the state parliament. However, the numbers have
dwindled to just five since the election and in January, five
resigned to sit as independents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
