<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Most U.S. Web Users Do Not Trust Sites They Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 18 (Xinhua) -- A majority of World Wide Web
users in the United States do not trust the sites they visit,
according to a report released Wednesday by an Internet market
research firm -- Jupiter Communications.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 64 percent of on-line consumers surveyed
do not think Web sites are trustworthy enough in following privacy
practices, including not passing user information on to third
parties.
</P>
<P>
Consumers' fears are fueled by government and media warnings
about the abuse of personal information passing over the Internet,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The consumers' fears are not easily assuaged despite the
majority of Web sites post some form of privacy policy.
</P>
<P>
Unless sites take action and educate and communicate with on-
line consumers, the research firm said, the fears will affect both
on-line advertising and digital commerce revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
