<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Severe Drought Hits North China's Shanxi Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 19 (Xinhua) -- Severe drought hits north China'
s Shanxi Province this year, affecting large area of crops and
leaving many people and domestic animals in a serious shortage of
drinking water.
</P>
<P>
This is the third consecutive year that Shanxi is stricken by
severe drought and autumn grain output this year is to drop, local
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Most parts of the province have been suffering from drought or
severe drought since the beginning of this year due to scant rain
water.
</P>
<P>
To make things worse, heat wave hit the province in August,
leaving more than three million people and 460,000 heads of
livestock in serious lack of drinking water.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, the drought affected 1.6 million
hectares of crops, which account for 68 percent of the province's
total planted area, with 210,000 hectares of crops completely
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Currently, major water conservation projects across the
province have only 414 million cubic meters of water in storage,
less than that in the drought-hit years of 1997 and 1998. Of the
province's small reservoirs, 60 percent are already dried up and
nearly 20,000 wells are reported to be in lack of water.
</P>
<P>
The city of Datong in northern Shanxi is the hardest-hit area
with 90 percent of its farmland affected by drought, the severest
in 50 years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
