<HEADLINE> Rafter Survives at RCA Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Australia's Patrick Rafter
contemplated pulling out of this week's RCA Championships with a
nagging right shoulder injury in Indianapolis, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Seeded second, Rafter was pushed to the limit by 105th-ranked
Anthony Dupuis of France before gutting out a 2-6, 6-2, 7-6 (7-1)
second-round victory Wednesday at the $745,000 hardcourt event.
</P>
<P>
Coming off a victory over Rafter in the final of the ATP
Championship in Cincinnati, world No.1 and top seed Pete Sampras
of the United States puts his 22-match winning streak on the line
tonight against Frenchman Guillaume Raoux.
</P>
<P>
The two-time defending U.S. Open champion, Rafter decided to
test his ailing shoulder rather than take a week off to rest it
before the final grand slam event of the year begins in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
But Rafter struggled early on against Dupuis, losing his serve
twice in the opening set before buckling down. The Australian
never faced a break point in the final two sets as he pulled out
the victory in just over two hours.
</P>
<P>
In other second-round action, sixth seed Marcelo Rios of Chile
was victorious in his return from injury as he struggled past
Israeli qualifier Harel Levy 6-2, 7-6 (7-5). A former world No. 1,
Rios missed three straight tournaments after a bout with groin and
hip tendon.
</P>
<P>
Also, Jan Siemerink of the Netherlands surprised seventh seed
Tommy Haas of Germany 6-3, 7-5; No. 11 Nicolas Lapentti of Ecuador
stormed past American qualifier Jared Palmer 6-2, 6-2; Sebastien
Grosjean of France edged No. 12 Albert Costa of Spain 6-7 (0-7), 6-
2, 7-5; and No. 14 Cedric Pioline of France crushed Alberto Martin
of Spain 6-0, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Alex Corretja of Spain, who dropped a second-
round match to Michael Chang last week in Cincinnati, is playing
at the Legg Mason Tennis Classic in Washington. Andre Agassi, last
year's runner-up, also is in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
