<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, August 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli and Palestinian negotiations centering on
the issue of Palestinian prisoners broke down Wednesday evening,
with the two sides disputing over how many security prisoners
jailed for anti-Israel activities should be released.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's envoy Gilad Sher told chief
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat in the talks that Israel would
not change its criterion for the release of prisoners at this
stage, but would review the issue in individual bases in the
future, according to a statement issued by the Prime Minister's
Office after the talks. (Israel-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said Wednesday that India's
draft nuclear doctrine was designed to build a nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
"We find it a document that describes the desire to develop a
nuclear arsenal and that is something that we think is not in the
security interests of India, the subcontinent or the United States
or the world," State Department spokesman James Rubin said at a
briefing. (US-India-Nuclear)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISTANBUL -- A group of women, wearing headscarves, squatted on
the ground beside the debris of a toppled six-floor building in
Aucilar, Istanbul late Wednesday night, praying for the three
children being rescued by relief workers from under the concrete.
</P>
<P>
It is still not known whether the three children are alive or
not as the three children have been trapped since the powerful
earthquake struck the area in the early hours of Tuesday. (Turkey-
Quake-Aftermath)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States Wednesday made a response to a
statement on the missile program by the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK), seeing it as a "window of opportunity"
for better relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
DPRK party secretary Kim Yong-sun told CNN in an interview this
week that Pyongyang was considering a less volatile missile policy,
but warned that if his country detected aggression against it, it
would retaliate. (US-DPRK-Missile)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The World Food Program has extended its five-
day food distribution program to displaced Afghans in Kabul for
two more weeks through August 26, a U.N. spokesman announced
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations currently estimates that 30,000 to 40,000
people have fled to Kabul, the capital, from the Shamali Valley
north of Kabul since the fighting between the Taliban and the
North Alliance forces began early this month. (UN-Afghanistan-
Fighting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
