<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy's Prosecutors Find No Charges Against Prodi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Italian judicial sources confirmed
Wednesday that the prosecutor's office of the Italian central city
of Bologna has so far found no misdeeds in inquiries into the
British Daily Telegraph's allegations that former Italian Premier
Romano Prodi failed to declare income from a series of consultancy
jobs.
</P>
<P>
The conservative British newspaper started the barrage of
charges against Prodi, a center-leftist, in May, when he was named
as the president-designate of the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
According to the Italian news agency Ansa, the judicial sources
said the inquiry, which is currently of a purely informative
nature with no list of suspects, began a couple of months ago, in
mid-June, as a "due act" required by law when allegations of a
certain gravity are advanced in a public form.
</P>
<P>
The English newspaper attacked Prodi in connection with the
consultancy company Analisi e Studi Economici s.r.l (ASE) owned by
him and his wife, and claimed in mid-June that he failed to
declare income received by ASE from consultancies in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
On August 4, the Daily Telegraph also claimed he had not
declared consultancy fees from the merchant bankers, Goldman
Sachs, and Unilever. The fees were allegedly paid into a Bologna
bank account held by ASE.
</P>
<P>
In 1996-97, the prosecutor's office investigated allegations
that Prodi had failed to declare profits from ASE, but the case
was shelved.
</P>
<P>
The latest inquiry has reportedly covered the same ground so
far and come up with the "no crime" answer.
</P>
<P>
The sources said investigation into the allegedly undeclared
sums from Goldman Sachs and Unilever should be complete by
mid-September by which time the European parliament is expected to
have voted its confidence in Prodi and the new European
Commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990819.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 </DATE_TIME>
