<HEADLINE> Wales Bid for FA Cup Is On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Welsh rugby boss Glanmor
Griffiths claimed Wednesday that he would "compete aggressively"
to bring the FA Cup final to Cardiff in two years.
</P>
<P>
Griffiths, also Welsh Rugby Union chairman, believes major
showpiece events will find a place at the new 72,000 all-seater
Millennium Stadium in years to come.
</P>
<P>
Wembley is being knocked down and rebuilt next year and
Griffiths will meet with Football Association commercial director
Philip Carling on Thursday to push his bid for the 2001 FA Cup
Final.
</P>
<P>
And, as Wales played their 'home' rugby internationals at
Wembley over the two years it has taken for the Millennium Stadium
to be completed, Griffiths claimed it is time to return the favour.
</P>
<P>
He said: "We have an infrastructure in Cardiff to stage such
events. We are also looking to get the European Cup Final in this
stadium.
</P>
<P>
"I am meeting with Philip Carling of the Football Association
tomorrow to talk about the terms and conditions of bringing the FA
Cup final here.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever we do for the FA Cup final, we will work closely with
the Football Association of Wales to get this event here.
</P>
<P>
"We will want to see what deal we can get from the FA but we
will bid aggressively for this."
</P>
<P>
Griffiths also wants other major sporting and entertainment
events switched to Cardiff and has targeted the rugby league cup
final, major world boxing championships and rock concerts.
</P>
<P>
The WRU allowed the old National Stadium to host events like
Wales' international football matches, soccer's Welsh Cup final
plus concerts including Michael Jackson and David Bowie. 
</P>
