<HEADLINE> Johnsen Sidelined by Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 18 (Xinhua) -- Manchester United defender Ronny
Johnsen could be out of action for the rest of the year if he has
surgery on both his knees.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian utility man has been sidelined all summer with a
condition known as "jumper's knee", which mainly affects
basketball players.
</P>
<P>
He spent the last three months at home on a rehabilitation
programme under the guidance of Norwegian FA team doctor Lars
Ingebretsen, but is now back in Manchester and says he is still in
pain.
</P>
<P>
He flew back to Norway at the weekend for another examination
and now United's club doctor Mike Stone is discussing the
situation with the Norwegian camp.
</P>
<P>
"We're waiting for Ronny to come back and see where we go from
there," said Sir Alex Ferguson. It is a dilemma."
</P>
<P>
Ingebretsen says: "United and Ronny will have to discuss the
possibility of an operation between themselves.
</P>
<P>
"He's worked hard during the summer and would like to get by
without an operation but he's still in pain while he's playing. I
don't know whether he has made his mind up yet whether to have
surgery."
</P>
<P>
Johnsen figured prominently in United's run-in to the Treble
last season when he took over from international teammate Henning
Berg at the center of the defence.
</P>
<P>
Signed from Turkish club Besiktas in the summer of 1996, he has
played in several positions for United specialising in midfield
and as partner to defender Jaap Stam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
